y:LGBT writers from the United States]]\n[[Category:Marxist writers]]\n[[Category:Women autobiographers]]\n<!--politics-->\n[[Category:Alabama socialists]]\n[[Category:American communists]]\n[[Category:American women Marxists]]\n[[Category:Black Marxists]]\n[[Category:California socialists]]\n<!--non-diffusing subcat-->\n[[Category:Lesbian politicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from the United States]]\n<!----political candidate---->\n[[Category:African-American United States vice presidential candidates]]\n[[Category:Communist Party USA politicians]]\n[[Category:Female United States vice presidential candidates]]\n[[Category:1980 United States vice-presidential candidates]]\n[[Category:1984 United States vice-presidential candidates]]\n<!--history circa 1960s-70s-->\n[[Category:Alternative Tentacles artists]]\n[[Category:American anti\u2013Vietnam War activists]]\n[[Category:Black Panther Party]]\n[[Category:COINTELPRO targets]]\n[[Category:FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives]]\n[[Category:Lenin Peace Prize recipients]]\n[[Category:People acquitted of kidnapping]]\n[[Category:People acquitted of murder]]\n<!--education-->\n[[Category:Brandeis University alumni]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Art Institute faculty]]\n[[Category:University of California, San Diego alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Santa Cruz faculty]]\n<!--places from-->\n[[Category:Academics from California]]\n[[Category:Activists from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:LGBT socialists]]\n[[Category:Philosophers from Alabama]]\n[[Category:Philosophers from California]]\n[[Category:Writers from Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Writers from Oakland, California]]\n<!--by centuries-->\n[[Category:20th-century African-American activists]]\n[[Category:21st-century African-American activists]]\n[[Category:20th-century African-American people]]\n[[Category:20th-century scholars]]\n<!--[[Category:21st-century academics]]-->\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American essayists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American essayists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American philosophers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American philosophers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:American Book Award winners]]\n[[Category:Anti-Zionism in the United States]]\n[[Category:African-American communists]]\n[[Category:Little Red School House alumni]]\n[[Category:American democratic socialists]]\n[[Category:Anti-Zionism]]\n[[Category:LGBT memoirists]]\n[[Category:African-American women academics]]\n", "name_user": "71.198.88.55", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eUniversity of Frankfurt)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angela_Davis"}
{"title_page": "Dartford Crossing", "text_new": "{{short description|Tunnel and bridge river crossing in Kent, UK}}\n{{Redirect|Queen Elizabeth II Bridge}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name          = Dartford Crossing\n| former names  = \n| image         = Dartford Crossing - geograph.org.uk - 1194694.jpg\n| caption       = Aerial view of the crossing looking northwards\n| opened_date   = November 1963 (western tunnel){{Clear}}May 1980 (eastern tunnel){{Clear}}October 1991 (bridge)\n| building_type = 2 tunnels{{Clear}}1 [[cable-stayed bridge]]\n| map_type      = United Kingdom Greater London\n| map_caption   = Location near London\n| coordinates   = {{coord|51|27|53|N|0|15|31|E|display=inline,title}}\n| location      = [[Dartford]], [[Kent]] {{Clear}} [[Thurrock]], [[Essex]]\n| height        = {{convert|61|m|ft}} (bridge deck)<br/>{{convert|137|m|ft}} (bridge tower)\n}}\n\nThe '''Dartford-Thurrock River Crossing''', commonly known as the '''Dartford Crossing''' and until 1991 the '''Dartford Tunnel''', is a major road crossing of the [[River Thames]] in England, carrying the '''A282''' road between [[Dartford]] in [[Kent]] in the south and [[Thurrock]] in [[Essex]] in the north. It consists of two bored tunnels and the [[cable stayed bridge|cable-stayed]] '''Queen Elizabeth II Bridge'''. The only fixed road crossing of the Thames east of [[Greater London]], it is the busiest estuarial crossing in the United Kingdom, with an average daily use of over 130,000 vehicles.{{sfn|Pickford|Blythe|2006|p=256}} It opened in stages: the west tunnel in 1963, the east tunnel in 1980 and the bridge in 1991. The crossing, although not officially designated a motorway, is considered part of the [[M25 motorway]]'s route, using the tunnels northbound and bridge southbound. Described as one of the most important road crossings in Britain, it suffers from heavy traffic and congestion.\n\nThe crossing's development started in the late 1930s, but was interrupted due to the [[World War II|Second World War]] and resumed in the 1950s. The original tunnel catered for a single lane of traffic in each direction, but rising traffic levels required the second tunnel to be built. The M25 connected to the tunnels at both ends when completed in 1986, and this increased traffic put pressure on the tunnels' capacity. A [[Private Finance Initiative]] scheme was started in 1988 to build the bridge. The combined crossing now handles four lanes of traffic in each direction.\n\nThe crossing had always been [[Toll road|tolled]], and from 1 April 2003 this became a [[Road pricing|charge]], though since 2008 it has been free from 10 pm to 6 am. An [[automatic number plate recognition]] charging scheme named the \"Dart Charge\" began in November 2014. As a result, the booths on the Kent side were removed and the charge is now only payable online. A residents' scheme is available, offering discounts for people living near the crossing.\n\n==Location==\nThe crossing spans the [[River Thames]] between [[Dartford, Kent]], to the south and [[Thurrock, Essex]], to the north. It is about {{convert|20|mi}} east of the [[centre of London]], outside the [[Greater London]] boundary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dartfordarchive.org.uk/technology/communication_drc.shtml|title=Dartford River Crossing: Innovation in Civil Engineering|first=Robert|last=Simpson|publisher=Dartford Town Archive|accessdate=12 July 2014}}</ref> The two tunnels are {{convert|1430|m}} long,<ref name=AATrust>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaa.com/public_affairs/reports/dartford_tunnel_test_2004.pdf|title=Tunnel Test 2004 \u2013 Dartford Tunnel|date=September 2004|page=3|publisher=[[AA Motoring Trust]]|accessdate=22 May 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108211825/http://www.theaa.com/driving-advice/driving-costs/dartford-crossing-dart-charge|archivedate=8 January 2017}}</ref> while the [[cable-stayed bridge]] is {{convert|137|m|ft}} high{{efn|For ships, the individual arch clearance is {{convert|54.1|m|ft}} and the main arch span clearance is {{convert|60.2|m|ft}}, both above [[mean high water spring]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pla.co.uk/Safety/Thames-Bridges-Heights|title=Thames Bridges Heights|publisher=Port of London Authority|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref>}} with a main span of {{convert|450|m|ft}}.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=_h39X2cspQ0C&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=dartford+crossing+450+metres#v=onepage&q=dartford%20crossing%20450%20metres&f=false|title=Bridge|first=Peter|last=Bishop|publisher=[[Reaktion Books]]|p=26|year=2008|isbn=978-1-861-89346-8}}</ref> A {{convert|50|mph|km/h}} [[speed limits in the United Kingdom|speed limit]] is in place in both directions.<ref name=limits>{{cite report|url=http://assets.highways.gov.uk/our-road-network/the-dartford-thurrock-river-crossing/A282_Dartford_Crossing_High_Winds_Protocol.pdf|title=Protocol for operating the A282 Dartford \u2013 Thurrock River Crossing during periods of strong winds|publisher=Highways England|accessdate=5 August 2016|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108173459/http://assets.highways.gov.uk/our-road-network/the-dartford-thurrock-river-crossing/A282_Dartford_Crossing_High_Winds_Protocol.pdf|archivedate=8 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>  The rail line [[High Speed 1]], between [[St Pancras International Station|St Pancras]] and [[Ebbsfleet International Station]]s, passes under the crossing approach roads on the north side of the river, at a near [[right angle]].<ref>{{cite map|title=East London, Billericay & Gravesend|id=Sheet 177|publisher=Ordnance Survey|scale=1:50,000}}</ref>\n\nThe design capacity is 135,000 vehicles per day, but in practice the crossing carries around 160,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theaa.com/motoring_advice/cost-of-motoring/dartford-crossing-dart-charge.html|title=Dartford crossing \u2013 Dart Charge|publisher=Automobile Association|date=23 November 2015|accessdate=5 August 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812211547/http://www.theaa.com/motoring_advice/cost-of-motoring/dartford-crossing-dart-charge.html|archivedate=12 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It has been described by the [[Highways Agency]] as \"a vital transport link for the national and South East economies\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/9904891.__25million_to_ease_hold_ups_at_Dartford_Tunnel/|title=\u00a325million to ease hold-ups at Dartford Tunnel|first=Lucy|last=Kirby|work=Kent Echo|date=31 August 2012|accessdate=5 July 2014}}</ref> by the former [[Secretary of State for Transport]], [[Patrick McLoughlin]], as \"a crucial part of the country's strategic road network\",<ref name=\"km_francis\">{{cite news|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/gravesend/news/two-thames-crossing-options--20197/|title=Two Thames crossing options|first=Paul|last=Francis|work=Kent Messenger|date=15 July 2014|accessdate=15 July 2014}}</ref> and by the local [[Thurrock (UK Parliament constituency)|Thurrock Council]] as \"one of Europe's most heavily used crossings and complex traffic management systems\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thurrock.gov.uk/thames-crossing/dartford-crossing-local-resident-scheme|title=Dartford Crossing local resident scheme|publisher=Thurrock Council|accessdate=5 August 2016}}</ref> It is signed as a major destination on London's orbital route, the [[M25 motorway|M25]], though the crossing and its approach road are an all-purpose road (the A282),{{efn|[[Highways England]] describe the crossing as \"a trunk road link (A282) in the M25 London orbital motorway\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highways.gov.uk/roads/road-projects/dartford-crossing-remote-payment-scheme/|title=Dartford Crossing Remote Payment Scheme|publisher=Highways England|date=February 2016|accessdate=8 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810223726/http://www.highways.gov.uk/roads/road-projects/dartford-crossing-remote-payment-scheme/|archive-date=10 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the crossing has been described as part of the M25 by [[Auto Express]]<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.autoexpress.co.uk/car-news/consumer-news/89626/drivers-face-up-to-3m-in-weekly-fines-on-the-dartford-crossing|title=Drivers face up to \u00a33m in weekly fines on the Dartford Crossing|journal=Auto Express|date=30 March 2016|accessdate=8 August 2016|quote=\"There are no longer any toll booths at the Dartford Crossing on the M25.\"}}</ref> and ''[[The Independent]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/m25-dartford-crossing-millions-of-motorists-face-fines-as-crossing-prepares-to-switch-from-toll-9846554.html|title=M25 Dartford crossing: Millions of motorists face fines as crossing prepares to switch from toll-bridge to 'free flow' system|newspaper=The Independent|date=7 November 2014|accessdate=8 August 2016}}</ref>}} allowing traffic prohibited from motorways to use it. Southbound traffic crosses the four-lane bridge, while northbound traffic uses both of the two-lane road tunnels. The bridge can be closed due to high winds<ref name=limits/> or maintenance. On these occasions, traffic uses the tunnels in both directions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/kent/news/closures-and-diversions-at-dartford-crossin-a104592/|title=Closures and diversions at Dartford Crossing|work=Kent Messenger|date=30 September 2008|accessdate=2 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Alternative routes===\nThe next nearest vehicle crossings to the west of Dartford are the [[Woolwich Ferry]] and the [[Blackwall Tunnel]], both well within East London.  When the bridge is closed in high winds and for maintenance, no convenient diversion exists through London for the higher-limit southbound vehicles. Those over {{convert|5.03|m|ft}} are diverted around the far side of the M25.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/dartford/news/dartford-crossing-gantries-17162/|title=Dartford Crossing to get tunnel and bridge closures as Dart Charge introduced and gantries installed near QEII bridge|first=Thom|last=Morris|work=Kent Messenger|date=14 May 2014|accessdate=2 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nA number of new crossings have been proposed as relief for the Dartford Crossing. The proposed [[Thames Gateway Bridge]] to the west was given planning permission by [[Transport for London]] (TfL) in December 2004,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2004/oct/20/communities.environment|title=Troubled waters|newspaper=The Guardian|date=20 October 2004|accessdate=6 December 2016}}</ref> but was cancelled in November 2008 when [[Boris Johnson]] became Mayor of London.<ref>{{cite press release| url = http://www.london.gov.uk/media/press_releases_mayoral/mayor-outlines-ten-year-plan-massive-transport-expansion| title = Mayor outlines ten year plan for massive transport expansion| date = 6 November 2008| accessdate = 11 July 2010| publisher = Transport for London| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110629165406/http://www.london.gov.uk/media/press_releases_mayoral/mayor-outlines-ten-year-plan-massive-transport-expansion| archivedate = 29 June 2011}}</ref> Johnson subsequently proposed the [[Gallions Reach Ferry]], a ferry crossing in the same location, as an alternative.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/comment/comment/andrew-adonis-boris-cant-put-off-a-new-thames-crossing-in-the-east-8653336.html|title=Boris can't put off a new Thames crossing in the east|author=[[Andrew Adonis, Baron Adonis|Andrew Adonis]]|newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=11 June 2013|accessdate=26 June 2013}}</ref> The [[Lower Thames Crossing]] is a proposed tunnel to the east between [[Shorne]], Kent and [[South Ockendon]], Essex.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-23237945|title=Lower Thames Crossing: 'More M25 misery' if option agreed|work=BBC News|date=15 November 2016|accessdate=6 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=bbc_39575467>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-surrey-39575467|title=Lower Thames Crossing route between Kent and Essex revealed|work=BBC News|date=12 April 2017|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref> [[Thurrock Council]] suggest that this crossing will be essential for managing congestion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-23237945|title=Tunnel recommended for new Thames crossing|work=BBC News|date=9 July 2013|accessdate=5 July 2014}}</ref> A public consultation on the scheme ended in March 2016, with the route announced in April 2017,<ref name=bbc_39575467/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://highwaysengland.citizenspace.com/cip/lower-thames-crossing-consultation|title=Lower Thames Crossing Consultation|publisher=Highways England|date=25 March 2016|accessdate=5 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/04/12/new-river-thames-road-crossing-route-unveiled/|title=New River Thames road crossing route linking Kent and Essex unveiled|date=12 April 2017|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=22 January 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\nthough Highways England do not expect to start construction before 2026.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/gravesend/news/new-thames-crossing-will-not-100138/|title=Campaigners insist Highways England's plans for a Gravesend Crossing will not help Dartford traffic|work=Kent Online|date=4 August 2016|accessdate=5 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Charges==\n[[File:Dartford Crossing Tolls - geograph.org.uk - 169071.jpg|thumb|Overhead view of the crossing looking northbound. The toll booths were replaced by electronic charging barriers in 2014.]]\n\nA [[Free-flow tolling|free-flow]] electronic charging system called '''Dart Charge''' began in November 2014 based on [[automatic number plate recognition]]. The charge can be paid online or phone in advance or by midnight the day after crossing, but can no longer be paid in cash at the site since the old toll booths have been removed.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = https://www.gov.uk/government/news/dart-charge-dartford-crossing-remote-payment|title = Dart Charge: Dartford Crossing remote payment|date = 1 December 2014|accessdate = 2 December 2014|website = Gov.uk|publisher = }}</ref> However, cash payments are accepted at some Payzone shops.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/pay-dartford-crossing-charge|title=Pay the Dartford Crossing charge (Dart Charge)|publisher=HM Government|accessdate=26 July 2017}}</ref> Reminder signs on approaches to the crossing say \"Dart charge; find us online. Pay by midnight tomorrow.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/458103/Essex.pdf|title=Dart charge : Essex charging signs|publisher=Highways England|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/458102/Kent_.pdf|title=Dart charge : Kent charging signs|publisher=Highways England|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref> Vehicles have to pay the charge if they use the crossing between 6&nbsp;am and 10&nbsp;pm seven days per week, and this is indicated on overhead-gantry signs. Daily charges for the crossing since October 2018 are:<ref name=\"dt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dart-tag.co.uk/nossl/home.php|title=Dart Tag|publisher=Highways Agency|accessdate=2 July 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715201955/http://www.dart-tag.co.uk/nossl/home.php|archivedate=15 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"km20141105\"/>\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ Day charges\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Vehicle class\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Pay-as-you-go\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Pre-paid accounts\n|-\n| Motorcycles\n| Free\n| Free\n|-\n| Cars, motorhomes, small minibuses\n| \u00a32.50\n| \u00a32.00<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/dartford/news/dart-charge-increased-by-20-187983/|title=Dartford Crossing: Dart Charge increasing to \u00a32 for account holders|work=Kent Online|date=1 October 2018|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2-axle buses, coaches, vans, goods\n| \u00a33.00\n| \u00a32.63\n|-\n| Multi-axle goods, coaches\n| \u00a36.00\n| \u00a35.19\n|}\n\nVarious categories of vehicles are exempt from the charge, including emergency services vehicles, military vehicles and those exempt from [[Vehicle Excise Duty]] on the grounds of disability.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dart-tag.co.uk/nossl/index.php?page=exemptscheme |title=Exempt scheme |publisher=Dart-tag.co.uk |accessdate=28 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110208014434/http://www.dart-tag.co.uk/nossl/index.php?page=exemptscheme |archivedate=8 February 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nThe charges vary according to the type of vehicle. Motorcycles are free but there are standard charges for cars, two-axle goods vehicles and larger vehicles with more than two axles.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dart-tag.co.uk/nossl/index.php?page=charges_and_discounts |title=Charges and Methods of Payments |publisher=Dart-tag.co.uk |accessdate=28 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110404010547/http://www.dart-tag.co.uk/nossl/index.php?page=charges_and_discounts |archivedate=4 April 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> Drivers who fail to pay the charge are issued with a penalty charge notice.<ref name=\":0\" /> There are no signs warning of penalty charges.\n\nSince 2008, a local residents' scheme gives 50 crossings to car drivers resident in the Dartford and Thurrock council areas for an annual registration fee of \u00a310, with additional crossings at 20p each.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dart-tag.co.uk/nossl/index.php?page=lrscheme |title=Local residents scheme |publisher=Dart-tag.co.uk |accessdate=28 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325152017/http://www.dart-tag.co.uk/nossl/index.php?page=lrscheme |archivedate=25 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> On 1 March 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/greater-discounts-for-4000-local-residents-at-dartford-thurrock-crossing |title=Greater discounts for local residents |publisher=gov.uk |date= |accessdate=11 March 2014}}</ref> this scheme was extended to include privately owned two-axle goods vehicles. A further option was introduced giving unlimited crossings for \u00a320 annually.<ref name=\"dt\"/> Around 44,000 drivers take advantage of this scheme each year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/record-number-of-local-residents-signed-up-for-dartford-crossing-discounts|title=Record number of local residents signed up for Dartford Crossing discounts|publisher=Highways England|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref> Although the website for paying the charge is operated by the UK Government, the day to day operations are run by French public roads operator [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des Autoroutes du Nord et de l'Est de la France]] (SANEF).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/dartford/news/crossing-deal-6624/|title=French firm awarded crossing deal|work=Kent Online|accessdate=9 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Western tunnel===\nThe idea of a tunnel crossing was first proposed by the [[Ministry of Transport (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Transport]] in 1924.<ref name='New Thames Tunnel'>{{cite news|newspaper=The Times|title=New Thames Tunnel|date=20 December 1924}}</ref> Initial reports at the start of the year suggested a crossing between [[Tilbury]] and [[Gravesend, Kent|Gravesend]], replacing a [[Gravesend\u2013Tilbury Ferry|ferry service]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1924/feb/28/gravesend-tilbury-tunnel#S5CV0170P0_19240228_HOC_172|title=Gravesend \u2013 Tilbury Tunnel|first=Harry|last=Gosling|date=28 February 1924|work=Hansard|accessdate=30 April 2014}},</ref> but this had been rejected by July in favour of a route further upstream, near Dartford.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1924/jul/31/air-force-estimates-1924-25#S5CV0176P0_19240731_HOC_441|title=Air Force Estimates 1924\u201325|first=Charles|last=Burney|date=31 July 1924|work=Hansard|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> By 1929, the total cost of building the tunnel had been estimated at \u00a33 million (equivalent to \u00a3{{inflation|UK-GDP|3|1929}} million in {{inflation-year|UK-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|UK-GDP}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1929/apr/16/thames-tunnel-scheme#S5CV0227P0_19290416_HOC_59|title=Thames Tunnel Scheme|first=Wilfrid|last=Ashley|date=16 April 1929|work=Hansard|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> The tunnel was planned to be part of a general orbital route around London and was provisionally known as part of the \"South Orbital Road\".{{sfn|TMA|2004|p=xxxii}}\n\n[[File:Dartford tunnel boring 1936.jpg|thumb|left|[[Tunnel boring machine]] used in the western tunnel, 1936.]]\n[[File:Dartford crossing approach.jpg|thumb|left|Northbound vehicles approaching the entrance to the western tunnel, with the bridge in the background]]\n\nThe first engineering work to take place was a [[compressed air]] driven pilot tunnel, which was drilled between 1936 and 1938.{{sfn|Jardine|McCallum|2013|p=246}} Work on the tunnel was delayed due to World War II, and resumed in 1959, using a [[Tunnelling shield|Greathead Shield]], similar to the work on the [[Blackwall Tunnel]] some 60 years earlier.{{sfn|Jardine|McCallum|2013|p=246}} The delay in work due to the war allowed the tunnel's design to be improved, which included a better ventilation system. After negotiations with the Ministry of Transport, Kent and Essex County Councils obtained government approval to charge tolls in 1960, before opening.{{sfn|TMA|2004|p=846}} The two-lane bore tunnel{{sfn|Banister|Berechman|2003|p=65}} opened to traffic on 18 November 1963;<ref name=AATrust/>{{sfn|Fautley|Garon|2004|p=263}} the total project cost was \u00a313 million (equivalent to \u00a3{{inflation|UK-GDP|13|1963}} million in {{inflation-year|UK-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|UK-GDP}})<ref name=\"km\">{{cite news|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/dartford/news/golden-birthday-for-dartford-tunnel-9011/|title=Golden birthday for Dartford Tunnel|work=Kent Messenger|date=18 November 2013|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> and it initially served approximately 12,000 vehicles per day.{{sfn|Banister|Berechman|2003|p=65}}\n\nThe toll was originally two [[Shilling (British coin)|shillings]] and [[Sixpence (British coin)|sixpence]], equivalent to 12.5p post-[[decimalisation]], and approximately equivalent in purchasing power to \u00a3{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|0.125|1963|{{inflation-year|UK}}}}}} in {{inflation-year|UK}}.{{Inflation-fn|UK}}<ref name=\"moate\">{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1984/feb/06/dartford-tunnel-bill-lords|title=Dartford Tunnel Bill|first=Roger|last=Moate|date=6 February 1984|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> The Dartford Tunnel Act 1967 gave Kent and Essex County Councils authority to change the tolls, and in December 1977, the toll was raised from 25p to 35p for cars, 40p to 55p for 2 axle goods vehicles, and 60p to 85p for HGVs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/47409/page/15818/data.pdf|title=Dartford Tunnel : Proposed Increase In Tolls|newspaper=London Gazette|date=16 September 1977|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref> By 1984, the toll for cars had risen to 60p.<ref name=\"moate\"/>\n\n===Eastern tunnel===\n[[File:Dartford Tunnel Ventilation Shaft - geograph.org.uk - 4416.jpg|thumb|A ventilation shaft to the north of the east tunnel]]\nThe first tunnel was expected to carry two million vehicles a year<ref name=\"km\"/> but by 1970 was carrying over eight million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/1975/jul/07/dartford-tunnel#S5CV0895P0_19750707_CWA_135|title=Dartford Tunnel|first=Neil|last=Carmichael|work=Hansard|date=7 July 1975|accessdate=25 May 2014}}</ref> That year, [[Michael Heseltine]], then a junior transport minister, announced that a second tunnel would be built in conjunction with the North Orbital Road, later to become the M25.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/1970/nov/20/dartford-tunnel-and-north-orbital-road#S5CV0806P0_19701120_CWA_157|title=Dartford Tunnel and North Orbital Road|first=Michael|last=Heseltine|work=Hansard|date=20 November 1970|accessdate=25 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nConstruction was approved in April 1971, with an initial expected opening date in 1976.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1971/apr/28/second-dartford-tunnel#S5CV0816P0_19710428_HOC_45|title=Second Dartford tunnel|first=Graham|last=Page|work=Hansard|date=28 April 1971|accessdate=25 May 2014}}</ref> Work was delayed due to a lack of funds, which was resolved by [[EEC]] funding granted in 1974.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/1975/apr/08/european-investment-bank-grants-london#S5CV0889P0_19750408_CWA_108|title=European Investment Bank Grants (London)|first=Edmund|last=Dell|work=Hansard|date=8 April 1975|accessdate=25 May 2014}}</ref> The second tunnel opened in May 1980, allowing each tunnel to handle one direction of traffic, by which time the joint capacity of the two tunnels had increased to 65,000 vehicles per day.{{Sfn|Banister|Berechman|2003|p=65}} Connection of the crossing to the M25 was completed on the northerly Essex side in September 1982 (Junction 31), and to the southerly Kent side in September 1986 (Junction 1a).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ciht.org.uk/motorway/m25stats.htm |title=The M25 \u2013 Statistics |publisher=Chartered Institute of Highway Technicians |accessdate=25 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525234033/http://www.ciht.org.uk/motorway/m25stats.htm |archivedate=25 May 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> Following the completion of the M25 in 1986, the daily demand had grown to 79,000 vehicles.{{Sfn|Banister|Berechman|2003|p=65}}\n\n===Queen Elizabeth II Bridge===\n<!-- [[Queen Elizabeth II Bridge]] redirects here -->[[File:Queen Elizabeth II Bridge - geograph.org.uk - 122668.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Each tower on the Queen Elizabeth II bridge is {{convert|137|m|ft}} high.]]\n\nDuring the early 1980s, it was anticipated that traffic through the tunnel would rise on the completion of the M25 in 1986. At the time, the expectation was that other routes in London would be improved instead, diverting 15% of traffic away from the tunnel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/1984/jun/19/dartford-tunnel#S6CV0062P0_19840619_CWA_43|title=Dartford Tunnel|first=Lynda|last=Chalker|work=Hansard|date=19 June 1984|accessdate=2 July 2014}}</ref> In 1985, the Transport Minister, [[Lynda Chalker]], announced that the number of toll booths would be increased to 12 each way, but concern grew that two tunnels would not be able to cope with the full demands of a completed M25.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1985/oct/21/dartford-tunnel#S6CV0084P0_19851021_HOC_460|title=Dartford Tunnel|first=Cyril|last=Townsend|first2=Nicholas|last2=Bonsor|first3=Lynda|last3=Chalker|work=Hansard|date=21 October 1985|accessdate=2 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nBetween September 1985 and December 1986, proposals for improvements to the Dartford Crossing underwent several changes,{{sfn|H.M. Stationery Office|1989|p=30}} and in 1986, a [[Trafalgar House (company)|Trafalgar House]] consortium won a bid to build a new bridge at Dartford crossing, valued at \u00a386 million (\u00a3{{inflation|UK-GDP|86|1986}} million in {{inflation-year|UK-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|UK-GDP}}).{{sfn|Banister|Berechman|2003|p=65}} At the time there were several other privately financed projects planned or under construction in the UK, including the [[Second Severn Crossing]]. From 1981 until the establishment of the [[Private Finance Initiative]]s (PFIs) in the late 1980s, private investment projects were governed by the [[Ryrie Rules]] which dictated that \"any privately-financed solution must be shown to be more cost-effective than a publicly-financed alternative, and that privately-financed expenditure by nationalised industries could not be additional to public expenditure provision\" [annual budget], \"which would be reduced by the amount of private finance borrowed.\"{{sfn|House of Lords: Select Committee on Economic Affairs|2010|p=9}}\n\nOn 31 July 1988, a Private Finance Initiative concession was enabled under the Dartford-Thurrock Crossing Act 1988, which transferred control of the crossing from Kent and Essex county councils to Dartford River Crossing Limited, a private company managed by Rodney Jones.{{sfn|The Institution|1992|p=10}} The company would also bear the debt of the bridge, then under construction, \"financed 100% by debt, with no equity contribution\".{{sfn|ITF|2013|p=42}}{{Efn|An alternative source says \"near\" 100% rather than 100% explicitly.{{sfn|Miller|Lessard|2001|p=177}}}} The private company was at risk of not recuperating their costs, but ultimately the Dartford scheme demonstrated that the Ryrie Rules were no longer a barrier to the private financing of public infrastructure projects.{{sfn|Hodge|Greve|Boardman|2010|p=529}} The concession was scheduled for 20 years from the transfer date, with a stipulation that it could end when debts had been paid off, which was agreed to have been achieved on 31 March 2002.{{sfn|HA|2014|p=5}} According to the ''International Handbook on Public-Private Partnership'', the chief financing for the project came from a \"20-year subordinated loan stock, 16-year loan stock and \u00a385 million (\u00a3{{inflation|UK-GDP|85|1988}} million in {{inflation-year|UK-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|UK-GDP}}) as a term loan from banks\".{{sfn|Hodge|Greve|Boardman|2010|p=529}}\n\nConstruction of the bridge started immediately after the creation of the PFI in 1988.<ref name=\"ha_about\">{{cite web|url=http://www.highways.gov.uk/our-road-network/managing-our-roads/improving-our-network/the-dartford-thurrock-river-crossing/about-the-crossing/|title=About the Crossing|publisher=Highways Agency|accessdate=2 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714153646/http://www.highways.gov.uk/our-road-network/managing-our-roads/improving-our-network/the-dartford-thurrock-river-crossing/about-the-crossing/|archive-date=14 July 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> It was designed by German civil engineer {{Interlanguage link multi|Hellmut Homberg|de}}, and the two main [[Caisson (engineering)|caissons]] supporting the bridge piers were constructed in the Netherlands. Each caisson was designed to withstand a bridge strike of a ship weighing up to 65,000 tonnes and travelling up to {{convert|18.5|kph|mph}}<ref name=\"et\">{{cite web|url=http://www.engineering-timelines.com/scripts/engineeringItem.asp?id=105 |title=Queen Elizabeth II Bridge |publisher=Engineering Timelines |accessdate=2 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714195958/http://www.engineering-timelines.com/scripts/engineeringItem.asp?id=105 |archivedate=14 July 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> The bridge deck is about {{convert|61|m|ft}} high, and it took a team of around 56 to assemble its structure. During construction of the approach road, a World War II bomb was found in its path, which required closure of the entire crossing.<ref name=\"pattison\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-15467112|title=The man who helped build the Dartford bridge|first=Jo|last=Pattison|work=BBC News|date=28 October 2011|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe bridge was opened by [[Queen Elizabeth II]] on 30 October 1991.{{sfn|TMA|2004|p=xiii}} The total cost of construction was \u00a3120&nbsp;million (\u00a3{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK-GDP|120000000|1990|r=-4}}}} in {{inflation-year|UK-GDP}}{{Inflation-fn|UK-GDP}}), including \u00a330 million (\u00a3{{inflation|UK-GDP|30|1991}} million in {{inflation-year|UK-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|UK-GDP}}) for the approach roads.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg13217924.900-bridge-design-stretched-to-the-limits-cablestayed-bridgesare-a-type-of-suspended-crossing-spare-but-functional-they-exploit-a-formof-bridge-engineering-that-is-bringing-down-the-cost-of-progressively-longercrossings-.html|title=Bridge design stretched to the limits: Cable-stayed bridges are a type of suspended crossing. Spare but functional, they exploit a form of bridge engineering that is bringing down the cost of progressively longer crossings|journal=New Scientist|number=1792|first=Bill|last=O'Neill|date= 26 October 1991|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> The proposed name had been simply the Dartford Bridge, but Thurrock residents objected and suggested the Tilbury Bridge, leading to a compromise.<ref name=\"pattison\"/> At the time of opening, it had the longest cable-stayed span of any bridge in Europe.<ref name=\"et\"/> It is the only bridge across the Thames downstream of Central London to be opened since [[Tower Bridge]] in 1894.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://motorwayarchive.ihtservices.co.uk/en/publication/visualisation--policy/part-8-direction-of-policy-towards-the-future/|title=The Dartford Crossing \u2013 Forerunner of the Private Finance Initiative|first=Alan|last=Bailey|authorlink=Alan Bailey|publisher=Chartered Institute of Highways Engineers|accessdate=6 July 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714171210/http://motorwayarchive.ihtservices.co.uk/en/publication/visualisation--policy/part-8-direction-of-policy-towards-the-future/|archivedate=14 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{{Wide image|Queen Elizabeth II Bridge, Dartford, England - Feb 2009.jpg|800px|The Queen Elizabeth II Bridge as viewed from Greenhithe, 1.5 miles (2.5km) east of the bridge in Kent|right}}\n\n===Charging scheme===\nIn 2000, the [[European Union]] issued a directive that [[value-added tax]] should be charged on all road tolls, including the Dartford Crossing. The Government opposed the directive and said it would bear the additional cost.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/922119.stm|title=Europe imposes road toll VAT|work=BBC News|date=12 September 2000|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> It was anticipated that the tolls would be removed on 1 April 2003 under the original PFI scheme contract. However, the Highways Agency decided that the tolls would become a \"charge\", under legislation introduced by the [[Transport Act 2000]] to introduce charging schemes on any trunk road bridge or tunnel at least {{convert|600|m|ft}} in length.{{sfn|HA|2014|p=5}}<ref>{{cite news| title = Motorists \"let down\" by toll u-turn|date = 1 April 2003|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2905225.stm|work = [[BBC News]]|publisher = BBC|accessdate = 27 February 2008|quote = \"From [1 April 2003] motorists should have been able to cross for free but the government's change of mind means car drivers still have to pay the \u00a31 charge. The AA Motoring Trust, a new charity linked to the AA said the government had broken its promise to scrap the toll. In 1996, the consortium behind the bridge proposed building a second bridge at no extra cost to the Treasury, on condition that the concession period was increased to allow them to recover their costs and generate a profit.\"}}</ref>{{Sfn|Banister|Berechman|2003|p=65}}\n\nUnder the 2000 Transport Act, the A282 Trunk Road (Dartford-Thurrock Crossing charging scheme) Order 2002 allowed the continuation of the crossing fee, which officially became a charge and not a toll on 1 April 2003. Management of the crossing was contracted to Le Crossing Company Limited on behalf of the Highways Agency.{{sfn|HA|2014|p=6}} In September 2009 the Highways Agency made a new contract with Connect Plus (M25) Limited. As well as maintaining the crossing, the contract required the company to widen around 40 miles of the M25 and to refurbish a tunnel on the [[A1(M)]] at [[Hatfield, Hertfordshire|Hatfield]].{{sfn|HA|2014|p=6}} In October 2009, the Government announced its intention to sell the crossing as part of a public sector deficit reduction strategy.<ref>\n{{cite news\n | title = Gordon Brown's fire sale of public assets to raise \u00a316bn\n | first = Allegra\n | last = Stratton\n | authorlink = Allegra Stratton\n | url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/oct/12/gordon-brown-public-asset-sale\n | newspaper = [[The Guardian]]\n | publisher = [[Guardian Media Group]]\n | location = [[London]]\n | date = 12 October 2009\n | accessdate = 11 July 2010\n | quote = Not all of the assets are surprising, with chancellor Alistair Darling announcing last month that the government intended to sell off the Dartford crossing as part of its attempt to meet the \u00a316bn target.\n }}\n</ref> The announcement was unpopular with local residents, who encouraged drivers to sound their horns in protest when using the crossing.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/england/8644336.stm|title=Dartford Crossing future in doubt|work=BBC News|date=26 April 2010|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref>  After the change of government following the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], the new [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|prime minister]] [[David Cameron]] announced that the crossing might still be sold, despite local opposition, particularly from [[Gareth Johnson]], [[Member of parliament#United Kingdom|member of parliament]] for Dartford.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsshopper.co.uk/news/8167032.DARTFORD__New_MP_vows_to_fight_Dartford_Crossing_sale_and_tolls/|title=DARTFORD: New MP vows to fight Dartford Crossing sale and tolls|work=News Shopper|date=16 May 2010|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> Subsequently, the chancellor [[George Osborne]] announced that charges would be increased instead to cover the budget deficit.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-11586160|title=Dartford Crossing toll charge to be increased|work=BBC News|date=18 June 2010|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> Pre-pay accounts for the crossing were introduced around this time; drivers held an [[electronic toll collection|electronic device]] called a DART-Tag in the vehicle that automatically deducted the charge at payment booths.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dart-tag.co.uk/nossl/index.php?page=faq|title=Dart Charge \u2013 FAQ|publisher=Dart Tag (official website)|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130325064246/http://www.dart-tag.co.uk/nossl/index.php?page=faq|archivedate=25 March 2013}}</ref> This was abolished when the Dart Charge was introduced in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/dart-charge-dartford-crossing-remote-payment|title=Dart Charge: Dartford Crossing remote payment|publisher=Highway Agency|date=16 December 2014|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nUnder the 2008 Charging Order introduced on 15 November 2008, charges between 10&nbsp;pm and 6&nbsp;am were discontinued, but standard daytime rates increased, starting at \u00a31.50 for cars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2008/1951/body/made?view=plain|title=The A282 Trunk Road (Dartford-Thurrock Crossing Charging Scheme) Order 2008|publisher=Highways Agency|date=21 July 2008|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> On 7 October 2012 the charges increased to \u00a32 for cars, \u00a32.50 for 2 axle goods vehicles and \u00a35 for multi-axle goods vehicles.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-18159668|title=Dartford Crossing toll charges set to rise|work=BBC News|date=22 May 2012|accessdate=6 December 2016}}</ref> By 2012, local businesses were complaining that the crossing's charge booths were impeding local growth. The government announced that a new electronic charging system would be introduced in 2014. Drivers would be able to pay by phone, text, online or in shops.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-20554969|work=BBC News|title=Businesses want Dartford Crossing toll booth removal speeded-up|date=30 November 2012|accessdate=4 July 2014}}</ref> The charge was proposed to increase to \u00a32.50 for cars, \u00a33 for two-axle goods vehicles and \u00a36 for multi-axle vehicles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/revised-charges-to-improve-dartford-crossing|title=Revised charges at Dartford Crossing |first=Mike|last=Penning|publisher=Department for Transport|date=22 May 2012|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref> Drivers not exempt and not paying the charge within 28 days are charged \u00a3105.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-20168817|title=Dartford Crossing fines up to \u00a3105 when barriers removed|work=BBC News|date=1 November 2012|accessdate=4 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nPreparation work on the free-flow scheme started in April 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-27102777|title=Dartford free-flow crossing work begins|work=BBC News|date=22 April 2014|accessdate=4 July 2014}}</ref> Concerns were raised about reliability, with a Highways Agency report predicting that it could lose up to \u00a36m of unpaid charges per year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-23334597|title=Dartford Crossing to lose '\u00a36m a year in unpaid tolls'|work=BBC News|date=17 July 2013|accessdate=4 July 2014}}</ref> In September, the Highways Agency announced that the new scheme would start to operate at the end of November, though related works to remove barriers would continue until April 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-29293449|title=Dartford Crossing cashless system date set|work=BBC News|date=20 September 2014|accessdate=25 September 2014}}</ref> Subsequently, the date for removal of the booths was confirmed as 30 November.<ref name=\"km20141105\">{{cite news|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/dartford/news/date-set-for-crossing-change-26502/|title=Dart Charge date fixed for November 30 when Dartford Crossing goes toll booth free|newspaper=Kent Messenger|date=5 November 2014|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Dart Charge scheme was considered a success by the project management, who claimed it has reduced peak-time round trips over the crossing by 15 minutes. [[The Automobile Association]] said the scheme had faults, while a BBC report showed 1.8 million fines had been issued for failure to pay in the year since the charge was set up.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-34968025|title=More than 1.8 million fines at Dartford crossing under Dart charge|work=BBC News|date=30 November 2015|accessdate=8 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Traffic==\nAs of 31 March 2014, a total of 1,486,929,267 journeys have been made. The highest recorded daily usage was 181,990 on 23 July 2004; since then traffic levels have decreased. From April 2013 to March 2014, there were 49,645,356 journeys; a daily average of 136,015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highways.gov.uk/our-road-network/managing-our-roads/improving-our-network/the-dartford-thurrock-river-crossing/traffic-flow/|title=Dartford \u2013 Thurrock River Crossing : Traffic flow|publisher=Highways Agency|accessdate=8 July 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714112503/http://www.highways.gov.uk/our-road-network/managing-our-roads/improving-our-network/the-dartford-thurrock-river-crossing/traffic-flow/|archivedate=14 July 2014}}</ref> The total income for the financial year ended 31 March 2012 was \u00a372,147,091, while the corresponding figure for the following financial year was \u00a380,331,662.{{sfn|HA|2014|p=6}} A 2016 report by Highways England suggested the crossing is used around 50 million times a year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lower-thames-crossing.co.uk/about/|title=Lower Thames Crossing \u2013 About|publisher=Lower Thames Crossing (official website)|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nBicycles are not permitted on the crossing, but cyclists can be carried across the crossing by the transport authority at no charge. Cyclists report to the crossing control offices on either side, using a free telephone service. The transfer takes around 15 to 30 minutes.<ref name=\"ha_top\">{{cite web|url=http://www.highways.gov.uk/our-road-network/managing-our-roads/improving-our-network/the-dartford-thurrock-river-crossing/|title=Improving our network : The Dartford \u2013 Thurrock River Crossing|publisher=Highways Agency|accessdate=4 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Dartford Tunnel bus.jpg|thumb|A bus designed to transport bicycles through the Dartford Tunnel in 1963]]\nIn October 1963, [[London Transport Executive|London Transport]] ordered five [[double-decker bus|double decker]] buses based on the Ford [[Thames Trader]] chassis for special duties, taking cyclists through the Dartford Tunnel. These had a lower deck purpose-built for carrying bicycles, with upper deck seats for cyclists. Access was via a stairwell to the upper deck starting several feet above the level of the road, accessible from special platforms built at either end of the tunnel; there was also a ladder built into the side of the bodywork for access elsewhere. The design was criticised for failing to protect any passenger from falling off the vehicle, and running costs were estimated at \u00a32,550 per month, with only \u00a345 revenue. The service was reduced to one bus in April 1964 and then cancelled in 1965, to be replaced by the current transfer service using a vehicle with a rear cycle rack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.nationalarchives.gov.uk/blog/ill-fated-cycle-bus/|title=The ill-fated cycle bus|first=Chris|last=Heather|publisher=[[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives]]|date=21 November 2013|accessdate=5 July 2014}}</ref> One of these buses has been preserved.<ref name=\"Thames Trader - Country Bus\">{{cite web|title=Thames Trader \u2013 Country Bus|url=http://www.countrybus.org/TT/TT.htm|work=Country Bus|accessdate=29 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe transport of hazardous goods through the crossing is governed by the European [[European Agreement concerning the International Carriage of Dangerous Goods by Road|ADR Agreement]]. The Dartford Crossing is class C, which restricts transporting goods such as nitrates and flammable liquids.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://intranet.rha.uk.net/docs/internet/hazardousgoods/ADR%20Tunnel%20Guide%2009.pdf|title=ADR Tunnel Codes explained|publisher=Road Haulers' Association|accessdate=11 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|url=http://www.unece.org/fileadmin/DAM/trans/danger/publi/adr/adr2011/English/Part2.pdf|title=ADR Classifications : Part 2|publisher=United Nations|page=103|accessdate=11 July 2014}}</ref> The introduction of the ADR scheme initially caused confusion, and for a short time, transporting aerosols through the tunnel was banned.<ref name=\"commercial motor\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.commercialmotor.com/latest-news/tunnel-troubles-hauliers-get-to-grips-with-adr-codes|title=Tunnel troubles: hauliers get to grips with ADR codes|first=Christopher|last=Walton|journal=Commercial Motor|date=3 August 2010|accessdate=5 July 2014}}</ref> Certain hazardous goods vehicles, together with some oversize and abnormal loads (if permitted) may require escorting by [[Highways Agency Traffic Officers]]. The crossing authority must hold exercises in conjunction with the [[emergency service]]s. In 2006 Exercise Orpheus was held, involving the closure of both road tunnels for five hours.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/kent/5065636.stm|title=Tunnels shut for safety exercise|work=BBC News|date=10 June 2006|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe tunnel is patrolled by Highways England Traffic Officers. Officers may stop and direct traffic on the crossing and its approach roads, and must be in uniform to exercise their powers.<ref name=\"S28\">{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1988/20/section/28|title=Dartford-Thurrock Crossing Act 1988 (section 28) |publisher=Ministry of Transport|work=National Archives|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref> The crossing's speed limit is enforced by [[speed camera]]s; between October 2012 and June 2014, 24,229 drivers were caught speeding, with some travelling as fast as {{convert|94|mph|km/h}} A spokesman from the Highways England said the cameras were \"helping us improve safety and make journeys more reliable\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-27746483|title=Thousands caught speeding on Dartford Crossing|work=BBC News|date=7 June 2014|accessdate=4 July 2014}}</ref> The bridge also has a reduced speed limit of {{convert|30|mph|km/h}} when [[crosswind]] is faster than {{convert|50|mph|km/h}} or headwind faster than {{convert|60|mph|km/h}}, and is closed entirely if Britain's national weather service, the [[Met Office]], predicts crosswind above {{convert|60|mph}} or headwind above {{convert|70|mph}}.<ref name=limits/>\n\n===Congestion===\nThe crossing is the busiest in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/dartfordthurrock-river-crossing-toll-charges-to-rise-7778496.html|title=Dartford-Thurrock River Crossing toll charges to rise|first=Peter|last=Woodman|work=The Independent|date=22 May 2012|accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sevenoakschronicle.co.uk/Dartford-Crossing-celebrates-golden-milestone/story-20094476-detail/story.html|title=Dartford Crossing celebrates golden milestone|work=Sevenoaks Chronicle|date=18 November 2013|accessdate=13 July 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714221443/http://www.sevenoakschronicle.co.uk/Dartford-Crossing-celebrates-golden-milestone/story-20094476-detail/story.html|archivedate=14 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Because the design capacity has been exceeded, the crossing is subject to major traffic congestion and disruption, particularly when parts are closed because of accidents or bad weather. Though the Government was adamant that the Queen Elizabeth II Bridge should be designed to avoid closure due to high winds,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1987/jul/09/dartford-thurrock-crossing-bill|title=Dartford-Thurrock Crossing Bill|work=Hansard|first=James|last=Couchman|date=9 July 1987|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> the bridge has nevertheless had to close on occasions. On 12 February 2014, during the [[Winter storms of 2013\u201314 in the United Kingdom|winter storms]], it was closed owing to {{convert|60|mph|km/h}} winds,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-26159208|title=QE2 Bridge at Dartford Crossing reopens after closure|work=BBC News|date=12 February 2014|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> and again on the evening of 13\u201314 February 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/local_news/basildon/11012099.Drivers_warned_of_QE2_Bridge_closure_this_evening/?ref=rss|title=30mph speed restriction on QEII bridge at Dartford crossing|work=Kent Echo|date=14 February 2014|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt busy times there was significant delay at the payment booths when these existed. Because there are numerous junctions on either side of the crossing, a high proportion of local traffic mixes with long distance traffic, for example travelling from the North and Midlands onwards to Continental Europe.{{sfn|Champion|1995|pp=91\u201392}} In 2004, a BBC survey reported that the crossing was \"the most stressful section of the M25\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/3541515.stm|title=Most stress at Dartford crossing|work=BBC News|date=8 March 2004|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> while in 2009, the crossing was listed in a [[Royal Automobile Club]] report as the fourth most congested road in Britain.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/kent/news/dartfords-crossing-misery-is-of-a98426/|title=Dartford's crossing misery is official!|work=Kent Messenger|date=27 April 2009|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref> Though Highways England have reported greatly improved journey times since automatic charging was introduced, [[Gareth Johnson]] MP claims otherwise and has insisted that the Lower Thames Crossing, along with improved signing around Dartford, are better options to reduce congestion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-34398780|title=Kent talks over Dartford crossing 'worst motorway'|work=BBC News|date=30 September 2015|accessdate=8 August 2016}}</ref> In 2015, he said the crossing was Britain's worst stretch of motorway.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-34424478|title=Better signage call for Dartford crossing, MP says|work=BBC News|date=3 October 2015|accessdate=5 October 2015}}</ref> There are agreed plans to create another crossing of the Thames in the East of London to ease congestion at the Dartford Crossing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/london/2018-05-10/new-bridge-crossing-given-go-ahead-in-east-london/|title=New river crossing given go-ahead in East London|website=ITV News}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Thames Gateway]]\n*[[Crossings of the River Thames]]\n*[[Tunnels underneath the River Thames]]\n\n==References==\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{notelist|30em}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Banister|first1=David|last2=Berechman|first2=Joseph|title=Transport Investment and Economic Development|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-JqRAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA65|date=29 August 2003|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-80270-7|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|title=The Motorway Achievement, Volume 1|editor-first=Ron|editor-last=Bridle|editor2-first=Peter|editor2-last=Baldwin|editor3-first=John|editor3-last=Porter|editor4-first=Robert|editor4-last=Baldwin|publisher=Thomas Telford|year=2004|isbn=978-0-7277-3196-8|ref={{harvid|TMA|2004}}}}\n*{{citation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wyxG9-pDeIoC&pg=PA90&dq=%22dartford+crossing%22+congestion+history|title=Bridge Modification: Proceedings of the Conference \"Bridge Modification\"|first=M.A|last=Champion|editor1-first=Brian|editor1-last=Pritchard|publisher=Thomas Telford|year=1995|isbn=978-0-7277-2028-3|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Fautley|first1=M.P.B.|last2=Garon|first2=J.H.|title=Essex Coastline: Then and Now|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_Hwl1Tefe1q4C|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_Hwl1Tefe1q4C/page/n262 263]|date=1 July 2004|publisher=Matthew Fautley|isbn=978-0-9548010-0-7|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Hodge|first1=Graeme A.|last2=Greve|first2=Carsten|last3=Boardman|first3=Anthony E.|title=International Handbook on Public-Private Partnership|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y_ySD3JABt0C&pg=PA529|date=1 January 2010|publisher=Edward Elgar Publishing|isbn=978-1-84980-469-1|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|author=House of Lords: Select Committee on Economic Affairs|title=Private finance projects and off-balance sheet debt: 1st report of session 2009\u201310, Vol. 1: Report|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IApxcY7wcUwC&pg=PA9|date=17 March 2010|publisher=The Stationery Office|isbn=978-0-10-845964-1|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|author=H.M. Stationery Office|title=M25 Review: The Report|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H7siAQAAIAAJ|year=1989|publisher=H.M. Stationery Office|isbn=978-0-11-550915-5|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|author=The Institution|title=Highways and Transportation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S_ZVAAAAMAAJ|year=1992|publisher=The Institution|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|author=ITF|title=ITF Round Tables Better Regulation of Public-Private Partnerships for Transport Infrastructure|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1SwDAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA42|date=26 September 2013|publisher=International Transport Forum, OECD Publishing|isbn=978-92-821-0395-1|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|title=Engineering and Health in Compressed Air Work: Proceedings of the International Conference, Oxford, September 1992|editor1-first=F.M.|editor1-last=Jardine|editor2-first=R.I.|editor2-last=McCallum|publisher=Routledge|p=246|year=2013|isbn=978-1-135-82609-3|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Miller|first1=Roger|last2=Lessard|first2=Donald R.|title=The Strategic Management of Large Engineering Projects: Shaping Institutions, Risks, and Governance|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M9aD1nqGgaoC&pg=PA177|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-0-262-26351-1|year=2001|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Pickford|first1=Andrew T. W.|last2=Blythe|first2=Philip T.|title=Road User Charging and Electronic Toll Collection|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R-JRAAAAMAAJ|date=1 October 2006|publisher=Artech House|isbn=978-1-58053-858-9|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/276504/9780108560040.pdf|title=Dartford-Thurrock River Crossing Charging Scheme : Account 2012\u20132013|publisher=Highways Agency|date=January 2014|accessdate=2 July 2014|ref={{harvid|HA|2014}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Dartford Crossing}}\n* [http://www.highways.gov.uk/our-road-network/managing-our-roads/improving-our-network/the-dartford-thurrock-river-crossing/ Dartford River Crossing website]\n* [http://www.gov.uk/dart-charge Dart-Charge] \u2013 website for toll pre-payment and credits\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XQYM69MbzKE British Pathe video of the first tunnel in 1957]\n\n{{ThamesCrossings| west=[[Dartford Cable Tunnel]]| east=[[High Speed 1]] }}\n{{Bridge\u2013tunnels}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Essex]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Thurrock]]\n[[Category:Places named after Queen Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II Bridge (Dartford Crossing})]]\n[[Category:Transport in Essex]]\n[[Category:Transport in Kent]]\n[[Category:Tunnels underneath the River Thames]]\n[[Category:Transport in the Borough of Dartford]]\n[[Category:Transport in Thurrock]]\n[[Category:Road congestion charge schemes in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Toll bridges in England]]\n[[Category:Road tunnels in England]]\n[[Category:Toll tunnels in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Tunnels completed in 1963]]\n[[Category:Tunnels completed in 1980]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1991]]\n[[Category:Tunnels in Essex]]\n[[Category:1963 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:M25 motorway]]\n[[Category:Bridge\u2013tunnels in Europe]]\n[[Category:Electronic toll collection]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Tunnel and bridge river crossing in Kent, UK}}\n{{Redirect|Queen Elizabeth II Bridge}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name          = Dartford Crossing\n| former names  = \n| image         = Dartford Crossing - geograph.org.uk - 1194694.jpg\n| caption       = Aerial view of the crossing looking northwards\n| opened_date   = November 1963 (western tunnel){{Clear}}May 1980 (eastern tunnel){{Clear}}October 1991 (bridge)\n| building_type = 2 tunnels{{Clear}}1 [[cable-stayed bridge]]\n| map_type      = United Kingdom Greater London\n| map_caption   = Location near London\n| coordinates   = {{coord|51|27|53|N|0|15|31|E|display=inline,title}}\n| location      = [[Dartford]], [[Kent]] {{Clear}} [[Thurrock]], [[Essex]]\n| height        = {{convert|61|m|ft}} (bridge deck)<br/>{{convert|137|m|ft}} (bridge tower)\n}}\n\nThe '''Dartford-Thurrock River Crossing''', commonly known as the '''Dartford Crossing''' and until 1991 the '''Dartford Tunnel''', is a major road crossing of the [[River Thames]] in England, carrying the '''A282''' road between [[Dartford]] in [[Kent]] in the south and [[Thurrock]] in [[Essex]] in the north. It consists of two bored tunnels and the [[cable stayed bridge|cable-stayed]] '''Queen Elizabeth II Bridge'''. The only fixed road crossing of the Thames east of [[Greater London]], it is the busiest estuarial crossing in the United Kingdom, with an average daily use of over 130,000 vehicles.{{sfn|Pickford|Blythe|2006|p=256}} It opened in stages: the west tunnel in 1963, the east tunnel in 1980 and the bridge in 1991. The crossing, although not officially designated a motorway, is considered part of the [[M25 motorway]]'s route, using the tunnels northbound and bridge southbound. Described as one of the most important road crossings in Britain, it suffers from heavy traffic and congestion.\n\nThe crossing's development started in the late 1930s, but was interrupted due to the [[World War II|Second World War]] and resumed in the 1950s. The original tunnel catered for a single lane of traffic in each direction, but rising traffic levels required the second tunnel to be built. The M25 connected to the tunnels at both ends when completed in 1986, and this increased traffic put pressure on the tunnels' capacity. A [[Private Finance Initiative]] scheme was started in 1988 to build the bridge. The combined crossing now handles four lanes of traffic in each direction.\n\nThe crossing had always been [[Toll road|tolled]], and from 1 April 2003 this became a [[Road pricing|charge]], though since 2008 it has been free from 10 pm to 6 am. An [[automatic number plate recognition]] charging scheme named the \"Dart Charge\" began in November 2014. As a result, the booths on the Kent side were removed and the charge is now only payable online. A residents' scheme is available, offering discounts for people living near the crossing.\n\n==Location==\nThe crossing spans the [[River Thames]] between [[Dartford, Kent]], to the south and [[Thurrock, Essex]], to the north. It is about {{convert|20|mi}} east of the [[centre of London]], outside the [[Greater London]] boundary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dartfordarchive.org.uk/technology/communication_drc.shtml|title=Dartford River Crossing: Innovation in Civil Engineering|first=Robert|last=Simpson|publisher=Dartford Town Archive|accessdate=12 July 2014}}</ref> The two tunnels are {{convert|1430|m}} long,<ref name=AATrust>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaa.com/public_affairs/reports/dartford_tunnel_test_2004.pdf|title=Tunnel Test 2004 \u2013 Dartford Tunnel|date=September 2004|page=3|publisher=[[AA Motoring Trust]]|accessdate=22 May 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108211825/http://www.theaa.com/driving-advice/driving-costs/dartford-crossing-dart-charge|archivedate=8 January 2017}}</ref> while the [[cable-stayed bridge]] is {{convert|137|m|ft}} high{{efn|For ships, the individual arch clearance is {{convert|54.1|m|ft}} and the main arch span clearance is {{convert|60.2|m|ft}}, both above [[mean high water spring]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pla.co.uk/Safety/Thames-Bridges-Heights|title=Thames Bridges Heights|publisher=Port of London Authority|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref>}} with a main span of {{convert|450|m|ft}}.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=_h39X2cspQ0C&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=dartford+crossing+450+metres#v=onepage&q=dartford%20crossing%20450%20metres&f=false|title=Bridge|first=Peter|last=Bishop|publisher=[[Reaktion Books]]|p=26|year=2008|isbn=978-1-861-89346-8}}</ref> A {{convert|50|mph|km/h}} [[speed limits in the United Kingdom|speed limit]] is in place in both directions.<ref name=limits>{{cite report|url=http://assets.highways.gov.uk/our-road-network/the-dartford-thurrock-river-crossing/A282_Dartford_Crossing_High_Winds_Protocol.pdf|title=Protocol for operating the A282 Dartford \u2013 Thurrock River Crossing during periods of strong winds|publisher=Highways England|accessdate=5 August 2016|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108173459/http://assets.highways.gov.uk/our-road-network/the-dartford-thurrock-river-crossing/A282_Dartford_Crossing_High_Winds_Protocol.pdf|archivedate=8 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>  The rail line [[High Speed 1]], between [[St Pancras International Station|St Pancras]] and [[Ebbsfleet International Station]]s, passes under the crossing approach roads on the north side of the river, at a near [[right angle]].<ref>{{cite map|title=East London, Billericay & Gravesend|id=Sheet 177|publisher=Ordnance Survey|scale=1:50,000}}</ref>\n\nThe design capacity is 135,000 vehicles per day, but in practice the crossing carries around 160,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theaa.com/motoring_advice/cost-of-motoring/dartford-crossing-dart-charge.html|title=Dartford crossing \u2013 Dart Charge|publisher=Automobile Association|date=23 November 2015|accessdate=5 August 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812211547/http://www.theaa.com/motoring_advice/cost-of-motoring/dartford-crossing-dart-charge.html|archivedate=12 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It has been described by the [[Highways Agency]] as \"a vital transport link for the national and South East economies\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/9904891.__25million_to_ease_hold_ups_at_Dartford_Tunnel/|title=\u00a325million to ease hold-ups at Dartford Tunnel|first=Lucy|last=Kirby|work=Kent Echo|date=31 August 2012|accessdate=5 July 2014}}</ref> by the former [[Secretary of State for Transport]], [[Patrick McLoughlin]], as \"a crucial part of the country's strategic road network\",<ref name=\"km_francis\">{{cite news|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/gravesend/news/two-thames-crossing-options--20197/|title=Two Thames crossing options|first=Paul|last=Francis|work=Kent Messenger|date=15 July 2014|accessdate=15 July 2014}}</ref> and by the local [[Thurrock (UK Parliament constituency)|Thurrock Council]] as \"one of Europe's most heavily used crossings and complex traffic management systems\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thurrock.gov.uk/thames-crossing/dartford-crossing-local-resident-scheme|title=Dartford Crossing local resident scheme|publisher=Thurrock Council|accessdate=5 August 2016}}</ref> It is signed as a major destination on London's orbital route, the [[M25 motorway|M25]], though the crossing and its approach road are an all-purpose road (the A282),{{efn|[[Highways England]] describe the crossing as \"a trunk road link (A282) in the M25 London orbital motorway\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highways.gov.uk/roads/road-projects/dartford-crossing-remote-payment-scheme/|title=Dartford Crossing Remote Payment Scheme|publisher=Highways England|date=February 2016|accessdate=8 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810223726/http://www.highways.gov.uk/roads/road-projects/dartford-crossing-remote-payment-scheme/|archive-date=10 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the crossing has been described as part of the M25 by [[Auto Express]]<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.autoexpress.co.uk/car-news/consumer-news/89626/drivers-face-up-to-3m-in-weekly-fines-on-the-dartford-crossing|title=Drivers face up to \u00a33m in weekly fines on the Dartford Crossing|journal=Auto Express|date=30 March 2016|accessdate=8 August 2016|quote=\"There are no longer any toll booths at the Dartford Crossing on the M25.\"}}</ref> and ''[[The Independent]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/m25-dartford-crossing-millions-of-motorists-face-fines-as-crossing-prepares-to-switch-from-toll-9846554.html|title=M25 Dartford crossing: Millions of motorists face fines as crossing prepares to switch from toll-bridge to 'free flow' system|newspaper=The Independent|date=7 November 2014|accessdate=8 August 2016}}</ref>}} allowing traffic prohibited from motorways to use it. Southbound traffic crosses the four-lane bridge, while northbound traffic uses both of the two-lane road tunnels. The bridge can be closed due to high winds<ref name=limits/> or maintenance. On these occasions, traffic uses the tunnels in both directions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/kent/news/closures-and-diversions-at-dartford-crossin-a104592/|title=Closures and diversions at Dartford Crossing|work=Kent Messenger|date=30 September 2008|accessdate=2 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Alternative routes===\nThe next nearest vehicle crossings to the west of Dartford are the [[Woolwich Ferry]] and the [[Blackwall Tunnel]], both well within East London.  When the bridge is closed in high winds and for maintenance, no convenient diversion exists through London for the higher-limit southbound vehicles. Those over {{convert|5.03|m|ft}} are diverted around the far side of the M25.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/dartford/news/dartford-crossing-gantries-17162/|title=Dartford Crossing to get tunnel and bridge closures as Dart Charge introduced and gantries installed near QEII bridge|first=Thom|last=Morris|work=Kent Messenger|date=14 May 2014|accessdate=2 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nA number of new crossings have been proposed as relief for the Dartford Crossing. The proposed [[Thames Gateway Bridge]] to the west was given planning permission by [[Transport for London]] (TfL) in December 2004,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2004/oct/20/communities.environment|title=Troubled waters|newspaper=The Guardian|date=20 October 2004|accessdate=6 December 2016}}</ref> but was cancelled in November 2008 when [[Boris Johnson]] became Mayor of London.<ref>{{cite press release| url = http://www.london.gov.uk/media/press_releases_mayoral/mayor-outlines-ten-year-plan-massive-transport-expansion| title = Mayor outlines ten year plan for massive transport expansion| date = 6 November 2008| accessdate = 11 July 2010| publisher = Transport for London| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110629165406/http://www.london.gov.uk/media/press_releases_mayoral/mayor-outlines-ten-year-plan-massive-transport-expansion| archivedate = 29 June 2011}}</ref> Johnson subsequently proposed the [[Gallions Reach Ferry]], a ferry crossing in the same location, as an alternative.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/comment/comment/andrew-adonis-boris-cant-put-off-a-new-thames-crossing-in-the-east-8653336.html|title=Boris can't put off a new Thames crossing in the east|author=[[Andrew Adonis, Baron Adonis|Andrew Adonis]]|newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=11 June 2013|accessdate=26 June 2013}}</ref> The [[Lower Thames Crossing]] is a proposed tunnel to the east between [[Shorne]], Kent and [[South Ockendon]], Essex.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-23237945|title=Lower Thames Crossing: 'More M25 misery' if option agreed|work=BBC News|date=15 November 2016|accessdate=6 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=bbc_39575467>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-surrey-39575467|title=Lower Thames Crossing route between Kent and Essex revealed|work=BBC News|date=12 April 2017|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref> [[Thurrock Council]] suggest that this crossing will be essential for managing congestion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-23237945|title=Tunnel recommended for new Thames crossing|work=BBC News|date=9 July 2013|accessdate=5 July 2014}}</ref> A public consultation on the scheme ended in March 2016, with the route announced in April 2017,<ref name=bbc_39575467/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://highwaysengland.citizenspace.com/cip/lower-thames-crossing-consultation|title=Lower Thames Crossing Consultation|publisher=Highways England|date=25 March 2016|accessdate=5 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/04/12/new-river-thames-road-crossing-route-unveiled/|title=New River Thames road crossing route linking Kent and Essex unveiled|date=12 April 2017|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=22 January 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\nthough Highways England do not expect to start construction before 2026.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/gravesend/news/new-thames-crossing-will-not-100138/|title=Campaigners insist Highways England's plans for a Gravesend Crossing will not help Dartford traffic|work=Kent Online|date=4 August 2016|accessdate=5 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Charges==\n[[File:Dartford Crossing Tolls - geograph.org.uk - 169071.jpg|thumb|Overhead view of the crossing looking northbound. The toll booths were replaced by electronic charging barriers in 2014.]]\n\nA [[Free-flow tolling|free-flow]] electronic charging system called '''Dart Charge''' began in November 2014 based on [[automatic number plate recognition]]. The charge can be paid online or phone in advance or by midnight the day after crossing, but can no longer be paid in cash at the site since the old toll booths have been removed.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = https://www.gov.uk/government/news/dart-charge-dartford-crossing-remote-payment|title = Dart Charge: Dartford Crossing remote payment|date = 1 December 2014|accessdate = 2 December 2014|website = Gov.uk|publisher = }}</ref> However, cash payments are accepted at some Payzone shops.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/pay-dartford-crossing-charge|title=Pay the Dartford Crossing charge (Dart Charge)|publisher=HM Government|accessdate=26 July 2017}}</ref> Reminder signs on approaches to the crossing say \"Dart charge; find us online. Pay by midnight tomorrow.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/458103/Essex.pdf|title=Dart charge : Essex charging signs|publisher=Highways England|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/458102/Kent_.pdf|title=Dart charge : Kent charging signs|publisher=Highways England|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref> Vehicles have to pay the charge if they use the crossing between 6&nbsp;am and 10&nbsp;pm seven days per week, and this is indicated on overhead-gantry signs. Daily charges for the crossing since October 2018 are:<ref name=\"dt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dart-tag.co.uk/nossl/home.php|title=Dart Tag|publisher=Highways Agency|accessdate=2 July 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715201955/http://www.dart-tag.co.uk/nossl/home.php|archivedate=15 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"km20141105\"/>\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ Day charges\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Vehicle class\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Pay-as-you-go\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Pre-paid accounts\n|-\n| Motorcycles\n| Free\n| Free\n|-\n| Cars, motorhomes, small minibuses\n| \u00a32.50\n| \u00a32.00<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/dartford/news/dart-charge-increased-by-20-187983/|title=Dartford Crossing: Dart Charge increasing to \u00a32 for account holders|work=Kent Online|date=1 October 2018|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2-axle buses, coaches, vans, goods\n| \u00a33.00\n| \u00a32.63\n|-\n| Multi-axle goods, coaches\n| \u00a36.00\n| \u00a35.19\n|}\n\nVarious categories of vehicles are exempt from the charge, including emergency services vehicles, military vehicles and those exempt from [[Vehicle Excise Duty]] on the grounds of disability.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dart-tag.co.uk/nossl/index.php?page=exemptscheme |title=Exempt scheme |publisher=Dart-tag.co.uk |accessdate=28 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110208014434/http://www.dart-tag.co.uk/nossl/index.php?page=exemptscheme |archivedate=8 February 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nThe charges vary according to the type of vehicle. Motorcycles are free but there are standard charges for cars, two-axle goods vehicles and larger vehicles with more than two axles.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dart-tag.co.uk/nossl/index.php?page=charges_and_discounts |title=Charges and Methods of Payments |publisher=Dart-tag.co.uk |accessdate=28 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110404010547/http://www.dart-tag.co.uk/nossl/index.php?page=charges_and_discounts |archivedate=4 April 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> Drivers who fail to pay the charge are issued with a penalty charge notice.<ref name=\":0\" /> There are no signs warning of penalty charges.\n\nSince 2008, a local residents' scheme gives 50 crossings to car drivers resident in the Dartford and Thurrock council areas for an annual registration fee of \u00a310, with additional crossings at 20p each.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dart-tag.co.uk/nossl/index.php?page=lrscheme |title=Local residents scheme |publisher=Dart-tag.co.uk |accessdate=28 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325152017/http://www.dart-tag.co.uk/nossl/index.php?page=lrscheme |archivedate=25 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> On 1 March 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/greater-discounts-for-4000-local-residents-at-dartford-thurrock-crossing |title=Greater discounts for local residents |publisher=gov.uk |date= |accessdate=11 March 2014}}</ref> this scheme was extended to include privately owned two-axle goods vehicles. A further option was introduced giving unlimited crossings for \u00a320 annually.<ref name=\"dt\"/> Around 44,000 drivers take advantage of this scheme each year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/record-number-of-local-residents-signed-up-for-dartford-crossing-discounts|title=Record number of local residents signed up for Dartford Crossing discounts|publisher=Highways England|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref> Although the website for paying the charge is operated by the UK Government, the day to day operations are run by French public roads operator [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des Autoroutes du Nord et de l'Est de la France]] (SANEF).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/dartford/news/crossing-deal-6624/|title=French firm awarded crossing deal|work=Kent Online|accessdate=9 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Western tunnel===\n[[File:Dartford tunnel boring 1936.jpg|thumb|left|[[Tunnel boring machine]] used in the western tunnel, 1936.]]\n[[File:Dartford crossing approach.jpg|thumb|left|Northbound vehicles approaching the entrance to the western tunnel, with the bridge in the background]]\nThe idea of a tunnel crossing was first proposed by the [[Ministry of Transport (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Transport]] in 1924.<ref name='New Thames Tunnel'>{{cite news|newspaper=The Times|title=New Thames Tunnel|date=20 December 1924}}</ref> Initial reports at the start of the year suggested a crossing between [[Tilbury]] and [[Gravesend, Kent|Gravesend]], replacing a [[Gravesend\u2013Tilbury Ferry|ferry service]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1924/feb/28/gravesend-tilbury-tunnel#S5CV0170P0_19240228_HOC_172|title=Gravesend \u2013 Tilbury Tunnel|first=Harry|last=Gosling|date=28 February 1924|work=Hansard|accessdate=30 April 2014}},</ref> but this had been rejected by July in favour of a route further upstream, near Dartford.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1924/jul/31/air-force-estimates-1924-25#S5CV0176P0_19240731_HOC_441|title=Air Force Estimates 1924\u201325|first=Charles|last=Burney|date=31 July 1924|work=Hansard|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> By 1929, the total cost of building the tunnel had been estimated at \u00a33 million (equivalent to \u00a3{{inflation|UK-GDP|3|1929}} million in {{inflation-year|UK-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|UK-GDP}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1929/apr/16/thames-tunnel-scheme#S5CV0227P0_19290416_HOC_59|title=Thames Tunnel Scheme|first=Wilfrid|last=Ashley|date=16 April 1929|work=Hansard|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> The tunnel was planned to be part of a general orbital route around London and was provisionally known as part of the \"South Orbital Road\".{{sfn|TMA|2004|p=xxxii}}\n\nThe first engineering work to take place was a [[compressed air]] driven pilot tunnel, which was drilled between 1936 and 1938.{{sfn|Jardine|McCallum|2013|p=246}} Work on the tunnel was delayed due to World War II, and resumed in 1959, using a [[Tunnelling shield|Greathead Shield]], similar to the work on the [[Blackwall Tunnel]] some 60 years earlier.{{sfn|Jardine|McCallum|2013|p=246}} The delay in work due to the war allowed the tunnel's design to be improved, which included a better ventilation system. After negotiations with the Ministry of Transport, Kent and Essex County Councils obtained government approval to charge tolls in 1960, before opening.{{sfn|TMA|2004|p=846}} The two-lane bore tunnel{{sfn|Banister|Berechman|2003|p=65}} opened to traffic on 18 November 1963;<ref name=AATrust/>{{sfn|Fautley|Garon|2004|p=263}} the total project cost was \u00a313 million (equivalent to \u00a3{{inflation|UK-GDP|13|1963}} million in {{inflation-year|UK-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|UK-GDP}})<ref name=\"km\">{{cite news|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/dartford/news/golden-birthday-for-dartford-tunnel-9011/|title=Golden birthday for Dartford Tunnel|work=Kent Messenger|date=18 November 2013|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> and it initially served approximately 12,000 vehicles per day.{{sfn|Banister|Berechman|2003|p=65}}\n\nThe toll was originally two [[Shilling (British coin)|shillings]] and [[Sixpence (British coin)|sixpence]], equivalent to 12.5p post-[[decimalisation]], and approximately equivalent in purchasing power to \u00a3{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|0.125|1963|{{inflation-year|UK}}}}}} in {{inflation-year|UK}}.{{Inflation-fn|UK}}<ref name=\"moate\">{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1984/feb/06/dartford-tunnel-bill-lords|title=Dartford Tunnel Bill|first=Roger|last=Moate|date=6 February 1984|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> The Dartford Tunnel Act 1967 gave Kent and Essex County Councils authority to change the tolls, and in December 1977, the toll was raised from 25p to 35p for cars, 40p to 55p for 2 axle goods vehicles, and 60p to 85p for HGVs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/47409/page/15818/data.pdf|title=Dartford Tunnel : Proposed Increase In Tolls|newspaper=London Gazette|date=16 September 1977|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref> By 1984, the toll for cars had risen to 60p.<ref name=\"moate\"/>\n\n===Eastern tunnel===\n[[File:Dartford Tunnel Ventilation Shaft - geograph.org.uk - 4416.jpg|thumb|A ventilation shaft to the north of the east tunnel]]\nThe first tunnel was expected to carry two million vehicles a year<ref name=\"km\"/> but by 1970 was carrying over eight million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/1975/jul/07/dartford-tunnel#S5CV0895P0_19750707_CWA_135|title=Dartford Tunnel|first=Neil|last=Carmichael|work=Hansard|date=7 July 1975|accessdate=25 May 2014}}</ref> That year, [[Michael Heseltine]], then a junior transport minister, announced that a second tunnel would be built in conjunction with the North Orbital Road, later to become the M25.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/1970/nov/20/dartford-tunnel-and-north-orbital-road#S5CV0806P0_19701120_CWA_157|title=Dartford Tunnel and North Orbital Road|first=Michael|last=Heseltine|work=Hansard|date=20 November 1970|accessdate=25 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nConstruction was approved in April 1971, with an initial expected opening date in 1976.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1971/apr/28/second-dartford-tunnel#S5CV0816P0_19710428_HOC_45|title=Second Dartford tunnel|first=Graham|last=Page|work=Hansard|date=28 April 1971|accessdate=25 May 2014}}</ref> Work was delayed due to a lack of funds, which was resolved by [[EEC]] funding granted in 1974.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/1975/apr/08/european-investment-bank-grants-london#S5CV0889P0_19750408_CWA_108|title=European Investment Bank Grants (London)|first=Edmund|last=Dell|work=Hansard|date=8 April 1975|accessdate=25 May 2014}}</ref> The second tunnel opened in May 1980, allowing each tunnel to handle one direction of traffic, by which time the joint capacity of the two tunnels had increased to 65,000 vehicles per day.{{Sfn|Banister|Berechman|2003|p=65}} Connection of the crossing to the M25 was completed on the northerly Essex side in September 1982 (Junction 31), and to the southerly Kent side in September 1986 (Junction 1a).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ciht.org.uk/motorway/m25stats.htm |title=The M25 \u2013 Statistics |publisher=Chartered Institute of Highway Technicians |accessdate=25 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525234033/http://www.ciht.org.uk/motorway/m25stats.htm |archivedate=25 May 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> Following the completion of the M25 in 1986, the daily demand had grown to 79,000 vehicles.{{Sfn|Banister|Berechman|2003|p=65}}\n\n===Queen Elizabeth II Bridge===\n<!-- [[Queen Elizabeth II Bridge]] redirects here -->[[File:Queen Elizabeth II Bridge - geograph.org.uk - 122668.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Each tower on the Queen Elizabeth II bridge is {{convert|137|m|ft}} high.]]\n\nDuring the early 1980s, it was anticipated that traffic through the tunnel would rise on the completion of the M25 in 1986. At the time, the expectation was that other routes in London would be improved instead, diverting 15% of traffic away from the tunnel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/1984/jun/19/dartford-tunnel#S6CV0062P0_19840619_CWA_43|title=Dartford Tunnel|first=Lynda|last=Chalker|work=Hansard|date=19 June 1984|accessdate=2 July 2014}}</ref> In 1985, the Transport Minister, [[Lynda Chalker]], announced that the number of toll booths would be increased to 12 each way, but concern grew that two tunnels would not be able to cope with the full demands of a completed M25.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1985/oct/21/dartford-tunnel#S6CV0084P0_19851021_HOC_460|title=Dartford Tunnel|first=Cyril|last=Townsend|first2=Nicholas|last2=Bonsor|first3=Lynda|last3=Chalker|work=Hansard|date=21 October 1985|accessdate=2 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nBetween September 1985 and December 1986, proposals for improvements to the Dartford Crossing underwent several changes,{{sfn|H.M. Stationery Office|1989|p=30}} and in 1986, a [[Trafalgar House (company)|Trafalgar House]] consortium won a bid to build a new bridge at Dartford crossing, valued at \u00a386 million (\u00a3{{inflation|UK-GDP|86|1986}} million in {{inflation-year|UK-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|UK-GDP}}).{{sfn|Banister|Berechman|2003|p=65}} At the time there were several other privately financed projects planned or under construction in the UK, including the [[Second Severn Crossing]]. From 1981 until the establishment of the [[Private Finance Initiative]]s (PFIs) in the late 1980s, private investment projects were governed by the [[Ryrie Rules]] which dictated that \"any privately-financed solution must be shown to be more cost-effective than a publicly-financed alternative, and that privately-financed expenditure by nationalised industries could not be additional to public expenditure provision\" [annual budget], \"which would be reduced by the amount of private finance borrowed.\"{{sfn|House of Lords: Select Committee on Economic Affairs|2010|p=9}}\n\nOn 31 July 1988, a Private Finance Initiative concession was enabled under the Dartford-Thurrock Crossing Act 1988, which transferred control of the crossing from Kent and Essex county councils to Dartford River Crossing Limited, a private company managed by Rodney Jones.{{sfn|The Institution|1992|p=10}} The company would also bear the debt of the bridge, then under construction, \"financed 100% by debt, with no equity contribution\".{{sfn|ITF|2013|p=42}}{{Efn|An alternative source says \"near\" 100% rather than 100% explicitly.{{sfn|Miller|Lessard|2001|p=177}}}} The private company was at risk of not recuperating their costs, but ultimately the Dartford scheme demonstrated that the Ryrie Rules were no longer a barrier to the private financing of public infrastructure projects.{{sfn|Hodge|Greve|Boardman|2010|p=529}} The concession was scheduled for 20 years from the transfer date, with a stipulation that it could end when debts had been paid off, which was agreed to have been achieved on 31 March 2002.{{sfn|HA|2014|p=5}} According to the ''International Handbook on Public-Private Partnership'', the chief financing for the project came from a \"20-year subordinated loan stock, 16-year loan stock and \u00a385 million (\u00a3{{inflation|UK-GDP|85|1988}} million in {{inflation-year|UK-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|UK-GDP}}) as a term loan from banks\".{{sfn|Hodge|Greve|Boardman|2010|p=529}}\n\nConstruction of the bridge started immediately after the creation of the PFI in 1988.<ref name=\"ha_about\">{{cite web|url=http://www.highways.gov.uk/our-road-network/managing-our-roads/improving-our-network/the-dartford-thurrock-river-crossing/about-the-crossing/|title=About the Crossing|publisher=Highways Agency|accessdate=2 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714153646/http://www.highways.gov.uk/our-road-network/managing-our-roads/improving-our-network/the-dartford-thurrock-river-crossing/about-the-crossing/|archive-date=14 July 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> It was designed by German civil engineer {{Interlanguage link multi|Hellmut Homberg|de}}, and the two main [[Caisson (engineering)|caissons]] supporting the bridge piers were constructed in the Netherlands. Each caisson was designed to withstand a bridge strike of a ship weighing up to 65,000 tonnes and travelling up to {{convert|18.5|kph|mph}}<ref name=\"et\">{{cite web|url=http://www.engineering-timelines.com/scripts/engineeringItem.asp?id=105 |title=Queen Elizabeth II Bridge |publisher=Engineering Timelines |accessdate=2 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714195958/http://www.engineering-timelines.com/scripts/engineeringItem.asp?id=105 |archivedate=14 July 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> The bridge deck is about {{convert|61|m|ft}} high, and it took a team of around 56 to assemble its structure. During construction of the approach road, a World War II bomb was found in its path, which required closure of the entire crossing.<ref name=\"pattison\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-15467112|title=The man who helped build the Dartford bridge|first=Jo|last=Pattison|work=BBC News|date=28 October 2011|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe bridge was opened by [[Queen Elizabeth II]] on 30 October 1991.{{sfn|TMA|2004|p=xiii}} The total cost of construction was \u00a3120&nbsp;million (\u00a3{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK-GDP|120000000|1990|r=-4}}}} in {{inflation-year|UK-GDP}}{{Inflation-fn|UK-GDP}}), including \u00a330 million (\u00a3{{inflation|UK-GDP|30|1991}} million in {{inflation-year|UK-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|UK-GDP}}) for the approach roads.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg13217924.900-bridge-design-stretched-to-the-limits-cablestayed-bridgesare-a-type-of-suspended-crossing-spare-but-functional-they-exploit-a-formof-bridge-engineering-that-is-bringing-down-the-cost-of-progressively-longercrossings-.html|title=Bridge design stretched to the limits: Cable-stayed bridges are a type of suspended crossing. Spare but functional, they exploit a form of bridge engineering that is bringing down the cost of progressively longer crossings|journal=New Scientist|number=1792|first=Bill|last=O'Neill|date= 26 October 1991|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> The proposed name had been simply the Dartford Bridge, but Thurrock residents objected and suggested the Tilbury Bridge, leading to a compromise.<ref name=\"pattison\"/> At the time of opening, it had the longest cable-stayed span of any bridge in Europe.<ref name=\"et\"/> It is the only bridge across the Thames downstream of Central London to be opened since [[Tower Bridge]] in 1894.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://motorwayarchive.ihtservices.co.uk/en/publication/visualisation--policy/part-8-direction-of-policy-towards-the-future/|title=The Dartford Crossing \u2013 Forerunner of the Private Finance Initiative|first=Alan|last=Bailey|authorlink=Alan Bailey|publisher=Chartered Institute of Highways Engineers|accessdate=6 July 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714171210/http://motorwayarchive.ihtservices.co.uk/en/publication/visualisation--policy/part-8-direction-of-policy-towards-the-future/|archivedate=14 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{{Wide image|Queen Elizabeth II Bridge, Dartford, England - Feb 2009.jpg|800px|The Queen Elizabeth II Bridge as viewed from Greenhithe, 1.5 miles (2.5km) east of the bridge in Kent|right}}\n\n===Charging scheme===\nIn 2000, the [[European Union]] issued a directive that [[value-added tax]] should be charged on all road tolls, including the Dartford Crossing. The Government opposed the directive and said it would bear the additional cost.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/922119.stm|title=Europe imposes road toll VAT|work=BBC News|date=12 September 2000|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> It was anticipated that the tolls would be removed on 1 April 2003 under the original PFI scheme contract. However, the Highways Agency decided that the tolls would become a \"charge\", under legislation introduced by the [[Transport Act 2000]] to introduce charging schemes on any trunk road bridge or tunnel at least {{convert|600|m|ft}} in length.{{sfn|HA|2014|p=5}}<ref>{{cite news| title = Motorists \"let down\" by toll u-turn|date = 1 April 2003|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2905225.stm|work = [[BBC News]]|publisher = BBC|accessdate = 27 February 2008|quote = \"From [1 April 2003] motorists should have been able to cross for free but the government's change of mind means car drivers still have to pay the \u00a31 charge. The AA Motoring Trust, a new charity linked to the AA said the government had broken its promise to scrap the toll. In 1996, the consortium behind the bridge proposed building a second bridge at no extra cost to the Treasury, on condition that the concession period was increased to allow them to recover their costs and generate a profit.\"}}</ref>{{Sfn|Banister|Berechman|2003|p=65}}\n\nUnder the 2000 Transport Act, the A282 Trunk Road (Dartford-Thurrock Crossing charging scheme) Order 2002 allowed the continuation of the crossing fee, which officially became a charge and not a toll on 1 April 2003. Management of the crossing was contracted to Le Crossing Company Limited on behalf of the Highways Agency.{{sfn|HA|2014|p=6}} In September 2009 the Highways Agency made a new contract with Connect Plus (M25) Limited. As well as maintaining the crossing, the contract required the company to widen around 40 miles of the M25 and to refurbish a tunnel on the [[A1(M)]] at [[Hatfield, Hertfordshire|Hatfield]].{{sfn|HA|2014|p=6}} In October 2009, the Government announced its intention to sell the crossing as part of a public sector deficit reduction strategy.<ref>\n{{cite news\n | title = Gordon Brown's fire sale of public assets to raise \u00a316bn\n | first = Allegra\n | last = Stratton\n | authorlink = Allegra Stratton\n | url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/oct/12/gordon-brown-public-asset-sale\n | newspaper = [[The Guardian]]\n | publisher = [[Guardian Media Group]]\n | location = [[London]]\n | date = 12 October 2009\n | accessdate = 11 July 2010\n | quote = Not all of the assets are surprising, with chancellor Alistair Darling announcing last month that the government intended to sell off the Dartford crossing as part of its attempt to meet the \u00a316bn target.\n }}\n</ref> The announcement was unpopular with local residents, who encouraged drivers to sound their horns in protest when using the crossing.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/england/8644336.stm|title=Dartford Crossing future in doubt|work=BBC News|date=26 April 2010|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref>  After the change of government following the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], the new [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|prime minister]] [[David Cameron]] announced that the crossing might still be sold, despite local opposition, particularly from [[Gareth Johnson]], [[Member of parliament#United Kingdom|member of parliament]] for Dartford.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsshopper.co.uk/news/8167032.DARTFORD__New_MP_vows_to_fight_Dartford_Crossing_sale_and_tolls/|title=DARTFORD: New MP vows to fight Dartford Crossing sale and tolls|work=News Shopper|date=16 May 2010|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> Subsequently, the chancellor [[George Osborne]] announced that charges would be increased instead to cover the budget deficit.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-11586160|title=Dartford Crossing toll charge to be increased|work=BBC News|date=18 June 2010|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> Pre-pay accounts for the crossing were introduced around this time; drivers held an [[electronic toll collection|electronic device]] called a DART-Tag in the vehicle that automatically deducted the charge at payment booths.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dart-tag.co.uk/nossl/index.php?page=faq|title=Dart Charge \u2013 FAQ|publisher=Dart Tag (official website)|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130325064246/http://www.dart-tag.co.uk/nossl/index.php?page=faq|archivedate=25 March 2013}}</ref> This was abolished when the Dart Charge was introduced in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/dart-charge-dartford-crossing-remote-payment|title=Dart Charge: Dartford Crossing remote payment|publisher=Highway Agency|date=16 December 2014|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nUnder the 2008 Charging Order introduced on 15 November 2008, charges between 10&nbsp;pm and 6&nbsp;am were discontinued, but standard daytime rates increased, starting at \u00a31.50 for cars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2008/1951/body/made?view=plain|title=The A282 Trunk Road (Dartford-Thurrock Crossing Charging Scheme) Order 2008|publisher=Highways Agency|date=21 July 2008|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> On 7 October 2012 the charges increased to \u00a32 for cars, \u00a32.50 for 2 axle goods vehicles and \u00a35 for multi-axle goods vehicles.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-18159668|title=Dartford Crossing toll charges set to rise|work=BBC News|date=22 May 2012|accessdate=6 December 2016}}</ref> By 2012, local businesses were complaining that the crossing's charge booths were impeding local growth. The government announced that a new electronic charging system would be introduced in 2014. Drivers would be able to pay by phone, text, online or in shops.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-20554969|work=BBC News|title=Businesses want Dartford Crossing toll booth removal speeded-up|date=30 November 2012|accessdate=4 July 2014}}</ref> The charge was proposed to increase to \u00a32.50 for cars, \u00a33 for two-axle goods vehicles and \u00a36 for multi-axle vehicles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/revised-charges-to-improve-dartford-crossing|title=Revised charges at Dartford Crossing |first=Mike|last=Penning|publisher=Department for Transport|date=22 May 2012|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref> Drivers not exempt and not paying the charge within 28 days are charged \u00a3105.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-20168817|title=Dartford Crossing fines up to \u00a3105 when barriers removed|work=BBC News|date=1 November 2012|accessdate=4 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nPreparation work on the free-flow scheme started in April 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-27102777|title=Dartford free-flow crossing work begins|work=BBC News|date=22 April 2014|accessdate=4 July 2014}}</ref> Concerns were raised about reliability, with a Highways Agency report predicting that it could lose up to \u00a36m of unpaid charges per year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-23334597|title=Dartford Crossing to lose '\u00a36m a year in unpaid tolls'|work=BBC News|date=17 July 2013|accessdate=4 July 2014}}</ref> In September, the Highways Agency announced that the new scheme would start to operate at the end of November, though related works to remove barriers would continue until April 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-29293449|title=Dartford Crossing cashless system date set|work=BBC News|date=20 September 2014|accessdate=25 September 2014}}</ref> Subsequently, the date for removal of the booths was confirmed as 30 November.<ref name=\"km20141105\">{{cite news|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/dartford/news/date-set-for-crossing-change-26502/|title=Dart Charge date fixed for November 30 when Dartford Crossing goes toll booth free|newspaper=Kent Messenger|date=5 November 2014|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Dart Charge scheme was considered a success by the project management, who claimed it has reduced peak-time round trips over the crossing by 15 minutes. [[The Automobile Association]] said the scheme had faults, while a BBC report showed 1.8 million fines had been issued for failure to pay in the year since the charge was set up.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-34968025|title=More than 1.8 million fines at Dartford crossing under Dart charge|work=BBC News|date=30 November 2015|accessdate=8 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Traffic==\nAs of 31 March 2014, a total of 1,486,929,267 journeys have been made. The highest recorded daily usage was 181,990 on 23 July 2004; since then traffic levels have decreased. From April 2013 to March 2014, there were 49,645,356 journeys; a daily average of 136,015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highways.gov.uk/our-road-network/managing-our-roads/improving-our-network/the-dartford-thurrock-river-crossing/traffic-flow/|title=Dartford \u2013 Thurrock River Crossing : Traffic flow|publisher=Highways Agency|accessdate=8 July 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714112503/http://www.highways.gov.uk/our-road-network/managing-our-roads/improving-our-network/the-dartford-thurrock-river-crossing/traffic-flow/|archivedate=14 July 2014}}</ref> The total income for the financial year ended 31 March 2012 was \u00a372,147,091, while the corresponding figure for the following financial year was \u00a380,331,662.{{sfn|HA|2014|p=6}} A 2016 report by Highways England suggested the crossing is used around 50 million times a year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lower-thames-crossing.co.uk/about/|title=Lower Thames Crossing \u2013 About|publisher=Lower Thames Crossing (official website)|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nBicycles are not permitted on the crossing, but cyclists can be carried across the crossing by the transport authority at no charge. Cyclists report to the crossing control offices on either side, using a free telephone service. The transfer takes around 15 to 30 minutes.<ref name=\"ha_top\">{{cite web|url=http://www.highways.gov.uk/our-road-network/managing-our-roads/improving-our-network/the-dartford-thurrock-river-crossing/|title=Improving our network : The Dartford \u2013 Thurrock River Crossing|publisher=Highways Agency|accessdate=4 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Dartford Tunnel bus.jpg|thumb|A bus designed to transport bicycles through the Dartford Tunnel in 1963]]\nIn October 1963, [[London Transport Executive|London Transport]] ordered five [[double-decker bus|double decker]] buses based on the Ford [[Thames Trader]] chassis for special duties, taking cyclists through the Dartford Tunnel. These had a lower deck purpose-built for carrying bicycles, with upper deck seats for cyclists. Access was via a stairwell to the upper deck starting several feet above the level of the road, accessible from special platforms built at either end of the tunnel; there was also a ladder built into the side of the bodywork for access elsewhere. The design was criticised for failing to protect any passenger from falling off the vehicle, and running costs were estimated at \u00a32,550 per month, with only \u00a345 revenue. The service was reduced to one bus in April 1964 and then cancelled in 1965, to be replaced by the current transfer service using a vehicle with a rear cycle rack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.nationalarchives.gov.uk/blog/ill-fated-cycle-bus/|title=The ill-fated cycle bus|first=Chris|last=Heather|publisher=[[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives]]|date=21 November 2013|accessdate=5 July 2014}}</ref> One of these buses has been preserved.<ref name=\"Thames Trader - Country Bus\">{{cite web|title=Thames Trader \u2013 Country Bus|url=http://www.countrybus.org/TT/TT.htm|work=Country Bus|accessdate=29 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe transport of hazardous goods through the crossing is governed by the European [[European Agreement concerning the International Carriage of Dangerous Goods by Road|ADR Agreement]]. The Dartford Crossing is class C, which restricts transporting goods such as nitrates and flammable liquids.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://intranet.rha.uk.net/docs/internet/hazardousgoods/ADR%20Tunnel%20Guide%2009.pdf|title=ADR Tunnel Codes explained|publisher=Road Haulers' Association|accessdate=11 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|url=http://www.unece.org/fileadmin/DAM/trans/danger/publi/adr/adr2011/English/Part2.pdf|title=ADR Classifications : Part 2|publisher=United Nations|page=103|accessdate=11 July 2014}}</ref> The introduction of the ADR scheme initially caused confusion, and for a short time, transporting aerosols through the tunnel was banned.<ref name=\"commercial motor\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.commercialmotor.com/latest-news/tunnel-troubles-hauliers-get-to-grips-with-adr-codes|title=Tunnel troubles: hauliers get to grips with ADR codes|first=Christopher|last=Walton|journal=Commercial Motor|date=3 August 2010|accessdate=5 July 2014}}</ref> Certain hazardous goods vehicles, together with some oversize and abnormal loads (if permitted) may require escorting by [[Highways Agency Traffic Officers]]. The crossing authority must hold exercises in conjunction with the [[emergency service]]s. In 2006 Exercise Orpheus was held, involving the closure of both road tunnels for five hours.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/kent/5065636.stm|title=Tunnels shut for safety exercise|work=BBC News|date=10 June 2006|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe tunnel is patrolled by Highways England Traffic Officers. Officers may stop and direct traffic on the crossing and its approach roads, and must be in uniform to exercise their powers.<ref name=\"S28\">{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1988/20/section/28|title=Dartford-Thurrock Crossing Act 1988 (section 28) |publisher=Ministry of Transport|work=National Archives|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref> The crossing's speed limit is enforced by [[speed camera]]s; between October 2012 and June 2014, 24,229 drivers were caught speeding, with some travelling as fast as {{convert|94|mph|km/h}} A spokesman from the Highways England said the cameras were \"helping us improve safety and make journeys more reliable\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-27746483|title=Thousands caught speeding on Dartford Crossing|work=BBC News|date=7 June 2014|accessdate=4 July 2014}}</ref> The bridge also has a reduced speed limit of {{convert|30|mph|km/h}} when [[crosswind]] is faster than {{convert|50|mph|km/h}} or headwind faster than {{convert|60|mph|km/h}}, and is closed entirely if Britain's national weather service, the [[Met Office]], predicts crosswind above {{convert|60|mph}} or headwind above {{convert|70|mph}}.<ref name=limits/>\n\n===Congestion===\nThe crossing is the busiest in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/dartfordthurrock-river-crossing-toll-charges-to-rise-7778496.html|title=Dartford-Thurrock River Crossing toll charges to rise|first=Peter|last=Woodman|work=The Independent|date=22 May 2012|accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sevenoakschronicle.co.uk/Dartford-Crossing-celebrates-golden-milestone/story-20094476-detail/story.html|title=Dartford Crossing celebrates golden milestone|work=Sevenoaks Chronicle|date=18 November 2013|accessdate=13 July 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714221443/http://www.sevenoakschronicle.co.uk/Dartford-Crossing-celebrates-golden-milestone/story-20094476-detail/story.html|archivedate=14 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Because the design capacity has been exceeded, the crossing is subject to major traffic congestion and disruption, particularly when parts are closed because of accidents or bad weather. Though the Government was adamant that the Queen Elizabeth II Bridge should be designed to avoid closure due to high winds,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1987/jul/09/dartford-thurrock-crossing-bill|title=Dartford-Thurrock Crossing Bill|work=Hansard|first=James|last=Couchman|date=9 July 1987|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> the bridge has nevertheless had to close on occasions. On 12 February 2014, during the [[Winter storms of 2013\u201314 in the United Kingdom|winter storms]], it was closed owing to {{convert|60|mph|km/h}} winds,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-26159208|title=QE2 Bridge at Dartford Crossing reopens after closure|work=BBC News|date=12 February 2014|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> and again on the evening of 13\u201314 February 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/local_news/basildon/11012099.Drivers_warned_of_QE2_Bridge_closure_this_evening/?ref=rss|title=30mph speed restriction on QEII bridge at Dartford crossing|work=Kent Echo|date=14 February 2014|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt busy times there was significant delay at the payment booths when these existed. Because there are numerous junctions on either side of the crossing, a high proportion of local traffic mixes with long distance traffic, for example travelling from the North and Midlands onwards to Continental Europe.{{sfn|Champion|1995|pp=91\u201392}} In 2004, a BBC survey reported that the crossing was \"the most stressful section of the M25\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/3541515.stm|title=Most stress at Dartford crossing|work=BBC News|date=8 March 2004|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> while in 2009, the crossing was listed in a [[Royal Automobile Club]] report as the fourth most congested road in Britain.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/kent/news/dartfords-crossing-misery-is-of-a98426/|title=Dartford's crossing misery is official!|work=Kent Messenger|date=27 April 2009|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref> Though Highways England have reported greatly improved journey times since automatic charging was introduced, [[Gareth Johnson]] MP claims otherwise and has insisted that the Lower Thames Crossing, along with improved signing around Dartford, are better options to reduce congestion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-34398780|title=Kent talks over Dartford crossing 'worst motorway'|work=BBC News|date=30 September 2015|accessdate=8 August 2016}}</ref> In 2015, he said the crossing was Britain's worst stretch of motorway.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-34424478|title=Better signage call for Dartford crossing, MP says|work=BBC News|date=3 October 2015|accessdate=5 October 2015}}</ref> There are agreed plans to create another crossing of the Thames in the East of London to ease congestion at the Dartford Crossing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/london/2018-05-10/new-bridge-crossing-given-go-ahead-in-east-london/|title=New river crossing given go-ahead in East London|website=ITV News}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Thames Gateway]]\n*[[Crossings of the River Thames]]\n*[[Tunnels underneath the River Thames]]\n\n==References==\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{notelist|30em}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Banister|first1=David|last2=Berechman|first2=Joseph|title=Transport Investment and Economic Development|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-JqRAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA65|date=29 August 2003|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-80270-7|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|title=The Motorway Achievement, Volume 1|editor-first=Ron|editor-last=Bridle|editor2-first=Peter|editor2-last=Baldwin|editor3-first=John|editor3-last=Porter|editor4-first=Robert|editor4-last=Baldwin|publisher=Thomas Telford|year=2004|isbn=978-0-7277-3196-8|ref={{harvid|TMA|2004}}}}\n*{{citation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wyxG9-pDeIoC&pg=PA90&dq=%22dartford+crossing%22+congestion+history|title=Bridge Modification: Proceedings of the Conference \"Bridge Modification\"|first=M.A|last=Champion|editor1-first=Brian|editor1-last=Pritchard|publisher=Thomas Telford|year=1995|isbn=978-0-7277-2028-3|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Fautley|first1=M.P.B.|last2=Garon|first2=J.H.|title=Essex Coastline: Then and Now|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_Hwl1Tefe1q4C|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_Hwl1Tefe1q4C/page/n262 263]|date=1 July 2004|publisher=Matthew Fautley|isbn=978-0-9548010-0-7|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Hodge|first1=Graeme A.|last2=Greve|first2=Carsten|last3=Boardman|first3=Anthony E.|title=International Handbook on Public-Private Partnership|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y_ySD3JABt0C&pg=PA529|date=1 January 2010|publisher=Edward Elgar Publishing|isbn=978-1-84980-469-1|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|author=House of Lords: Select Committee on Economic Affairs|title=Private finance projects and off-balance sheet debt: 1st report of session 2009\u201310, Vol. 1: Report|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IApxcY7wcUwC&pg=PA9|date=17 March 2010|publisher=The Stationery Office|isbn=978-0-10-845964-1|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|author=H.M. Stationery Office|title=M25 Review: The Report|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H7siAQAAIAAJ|year=1989|publisher=H.M. Stationery Office|isbn=978-0-11-550915-5|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|author=The Institution|title=Highways and Transportation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S_ZVAAAAMAAJ|year=1992|publisher=The Institution|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|author=ITF|title=ITF Round Tables Better Regulation of Public-Private Partnerships for Transport Infrastructure|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1SwDAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA42|date=26 September 2013|publisher=International Transport Forum, OECD Publishing|isbn=978-92-821-0395-1|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|title=Engineering and Health in Compressed Air Work: Proceedings of the International Conference, Oxford, September 1992|editor1-first=F.M.|editor1-last=Jardine|editor2-first=R.I.|editor2-last=McCallum|publisher=Routledge|p=246|year=2013|isbn=978-1-135-82609-3|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Miller|first1=Roger|last2=Lessard|first2=Donald R.|title=The Strategic Management of Large Engineering Projects: Shaping Institutions, Risks, and Governance|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M9aD1nqGgaoC&pg=PA177|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-0-262-26351-1|year=2001|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Pickford|first1=Andrew T. W.|last2=Blythe|first2=Philip T.|title=Road User Charging and Electronic Toll Collection|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R-JRAAAAMAAJ|date=1 October 2006|publisher=Artech House|isbn=978-1-58053-858-9|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/276504/9780108560040.pdf|title=Dartford-Thurrock River Crossing Charging Scheme : Account 2012\u20132013|publisher=Highways Agency|date=January 2014|accessdate=2 July 2014|ref={{harvid|HA|2014}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Dartford Crossing}}\n* [http://www.highways.gov.uk/our-road-network/managing-our-roads/improving-our-network/the-dartford-thurrock-river-crossing/ Dartford River Crossing website]\n* [http://www.gov.uk/dart-charge Dart-Charge] \u2013 website for toll pre-payment and credits\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XQYM69MbzKE British Pathe video of the first tunnel in 1957]\n\n{{ThamesCrossings| west=[[Dartford Cable Tunnel]]| east=[[High Speed 1]] }}\n{{Bridge\u2013tunnels}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Essex]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Thurrock]]\n[[Category:Places named after Queen Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II Bridge (Dartford Crossing})]]\n[[Category:Transport in Essex]]\n[[Category:Transport in Kent]]\n[[Category:Tunnels underneath the River Thames]]\n[[Category:Transport in the Borough of Dartford]]\n[[Category:Transport in Thurrock]]\n[[Category:Road congestion charge schemes in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Toll bridges in England]]\n[[Category:Road tunnels in England]]\n[[Category:Toll tunnels in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Tunnels completed in 1963]]\n[[Category:Tunnels completed in 1980]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1991]]\n[[Category:Tunnels in Essex]]\n[[Category:1963 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:M25 motorway]]\n[[Category:Bridge\u2013tunnels in Europe]]\n[[Category:Electronic toll collection]]\n", "name_user": "Liandrei", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWestern tunnel:moved imgs for better layout of text", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dartford_Crossing"}
{"title_page": "1956 Soviet nuclear tests", "text_new": "{{See also|List of nuclear weapons tests of the Soviet Union}}\n{{Infobox nuclear weapons test\n |name                = 1956\n |picture             = \n |picture_description = \n |country             = Soviet Union\n |test_site           = Ground Zero, Semipalatinsk, Kazakhstan; Kyzylorda, Kazakhstan\n |period              = 1956\n |number_of_tests     = 9\n |test_type           = air drop, dry surface, high alt rocket (30&ndash;80&nbsp;km), tower\n |max_yield           = {{convert|900|ktTNT|lk=in}}\n |previous_series     = [[1955 Soviet nuclear tests]]\n |next_series         = [[1957 Soviet nuclear tests]]\n}}\n{{GeoGroup|article=1956 Soviet nuclear tests}}\n\nThe '''Soviet Union's 1956 nuclear test series''' was a group of 9 [[nuclear test]]s conducted in 1956. These tests followed the ''[[1955 Soviet nuclear tests]]'' series and preceded the ''[[1957 Soviet nuclear tests]]'' series.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n |+ Soviet Union's 1956 series tests and detonations\n |-\n !style=\"background:#ffdead;\" | Name <ref group=note>The US, France and Great Britain have code-named their test events, while the USSR and China did not, and therefore have only test numbers (with some exceptions &ndash; Soviet peaceful explosions were named). Word translations into English in parentheses unless the name is a proper noun. A dash followed by a number indicates a member of a salvo event.  The US also sometimes named the individual explosions in such a salvo test, which results in \"name1 &ndash; 1(with name2)\". If test is canceled or aborted, then the row data like date and location discloses the intended plans, where known.</ref>\n !style=\"background:#efefef;\" | Date time ([[Universal Time|UT]])\n !style=\"background:#ffdead;\" | Local [[Time Zone|time zone]] <ref group=note>To convert the UT time into standard local, add the number of hours in parentheses to the UT time; for local daylight saving time, add one additional hour. If the result is earlier than 00:00, add 24 hours and subtract 1 from the day; if it is 24:00 or later, subtract 24 hours and add 1 to the day. </ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Time Zone Historical Database| publisher=iana.com| url=http://www.ietf.org/timezones/| accessdate=March 8, 2014}}</ref>\n !style=\"background:#efefef;\" | [[List of nuclear test sites|Location]] <ref group=note>Rough place name and a latitude/longitude reference; for rocket-carried tests, the launch location is specified before the detonation location, if known. Some locations are extremely accurate; others (like airdrops and space blasts) may be quite inaccurate. \"~\" indicates a likely pro-forma rough location, shared with other tests in that same area.</ref>\n !style=\"background:#ffdead;\" | [[Elevation]] + height <ref group=note>Elevation is the ground level at the point directly below the explosion relative to sea level; height is the additional distance added or subtracted by tower, balloon, shaft, tunnel, air drop or other contrivance. For rocket bursts the ground level is \"N/A\". In some cases it is not clear if the height is absolute or relative to ground, for example, ''Plumbbob/John''.  No number or units indicates the value is unknown, while \"0\" means zero. Sorting on this column is by elevation and height added together.</ref>\n !style=\"background:#efefef;\" | Delivery, <ref group=note>Atmospheric, airdrop, balloon, gun, cruise missile, rocket, surface, tower, and barge are all disallowed by the [[Partial Nuclear Test Ban Treaty]]. Sealed shaft and tunnel are underground, and remained useful under the PTBT. Intentional cratering tests are borderline; they occurred under the treaty, were sometimes protested, and generally overlooked if the test was declared to be a peaceful use.</ref><br />Purpose <ref group=note>Include weapons development, weapon effects, safety test, transport safety test, war, science, joint verification and industrial/peaceful, which may be further broken down.</ref>\n !style=\"background:#efefef;\" | [[List of nuclear weapons|Device]] <ref group=note>Designations for test items where known, \"?\" indicates some uncertainty about the preceding value, nicknames for particular devices in quotes. This category of information is often not officially disclosed.</ref>\n !style=\"background:#ffdead;\" | [[Nuclear weapon yield|Yield]] <ref group=note>Estimated energy yield in [[TNT equivalent|tons, kilotons, and megatons]]. A ton of TNT equivalent is defined as 4.184&nbsp;gigajoules (1&nbsp;gigacalorie).</ref>\n !style=\"background:#efefef;\" class=\"unsortable\" | [[Nuclear fallout|Fallout]] <ref group=note>Radioactive emission to the atmosphere aside from prompt neutrons, where known.  The measured species is only iodine-131 if mentioned, otherwise it is all species. No entry means unknown, probably none if underground and \"all\" if not; otherwise notation for whether measured on the site only or off the site, where known, and the measured amount of radioactivity released.</ref>\n !style=\"background:#ffdead;\" class=\"unsortable\" | References\n !style=\"background:#efefef;\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n |-\n ! ''25 Baykal (Joe 20)''{{anchor|25 Baykal (Joe 20)}}\n | {{dts|format=dmy|1956|2|2}}\n | style=\"text-align:center;\" | KIZT (5&nbsp;hrs)<br /> || Launch from Kapustin Yar, Astrakhan {{coord|48.56956|45.90346|name=Launch_25 Baykal (Joe 20)|display=inline}}, elv: {{convert|0|+|0|m|abbr=on}};<br />Detonation over Kyzylorda, Kazakhstan {{coord|47.984|62.011|name=25 Baykal (Joe 20)|display=inline}}\n | {{sort|000000|}}N/A + 0\n | high alt rocket (30&ndash;80&nbsp;km),<br />weapon effect\n | \n | style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{sort|000003000|300&nbsp;t}}\n | \n | <ref name=LT_228 /><ref name=LT_31 /><ref name=LT_19 /><ref name=LT_1 />\n | Full-scale test of R-5M rocket launched in Kapustin Yar, targeted near Priaralsk Karakum, Kazakhstan. A [[fizzle (nuclear test)|fizzle]].\n |-\n ! ''26 (Joe 21)''{{an