ntelligence Estimate 11-2A-62| url=http://www.foia.cia.gov/sites/default/files/document_conversions/89801/DOC_0000843187.pdf|title=Soviet Atomic Energy Program| accessdate=August 12, 2014| date=May 16, 1962}}</ref>\n<ref name=LT_1>{{cite techreport| last1=Yang| first1=Xiaoping| first2=Robert| last2=North| first3=Carl| last3=Romney|date=August 2000| title=CMR Nuclear Explosion Database (Revision 3)| publisher=SMDC Monitoring Research}}</ref>\n<ref name=LT_7>{{cite book| publisher=RFNC-VNIIEF| year=1996| title=USSR Nuclear Weapons Tests and Peaceful Nuclear Explosions 1949 through 1990| location=Sarov, Russia}} The official Russian list of Soviet tests.</ref>\n<ref name=LT_36>{{cite book| last1=Cochran| first1=Thomas B.| last2=Arkin| first2=William M.| first3=Robert S.| last3=Norris| first4=Jeffrey I.| last4=Sands| title=Nuclear Weapons Databook Vol. IV: Soviet Nuclear Weapons| publisher=Harper and Row| location=New York, NY}}</ref>\n<ref name=LT_52>{{cite techreport| title=Nuclear explosions in the USSR: The North Test Site reference material, version 4| date=December 1, 2004| publisher=IAEA Dept. of Nuclear Safety and Security| url=http://www-ns.iaea.org/downloads/rw/waste-safety/north-test-site-final.pdf| accessdate=December 13, 2013}}</ref>\n<ref name=LT_201>{{cite techreport|last1=Andrushkin |first1=Vitaly V. |first2=William |last2=Leith |date=September 1, 2001 |title=The containment of Soviet underground nuclear explosions |publisher=USGS |type=Open File Report 01-312 |url=http://geology.er.usgs.gov/eespteam/pdf/USGSOFR01312.pdf |accessdate=December 13, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130509080818/http://geology.er.usgs.gov/eespteam/pdf/USGSOFR01312.pdf |archivedate=May 9, 2013 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.newscientist.com/article/2125202-exposed-soviet-cover-up-of-nuclear-fallout-worse-than-chernobyl/ Exposed: Soviet cover-up of nuclear fallout worse than Chernobyl] at ''[[New Scientist]]''\n\n[[Category:Soviet nuclear weapons testing|1956]]\n[[Category:1956 in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:1956 in military history]]\n[[Category:Explosions in 1956]]\n", "name_user": "3Todd", "label": "safe", "comment": "Repair broken reference in note about times", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1956_Soviet_nuclear_tests"}
{"title_page": "Bellona (goddess)", "text_new": "{{short description|Roman goddess of war}}\n{{other uses|Bellona (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox deity\n| type             = Roman\n| name             = Bellona\n| image            = File:Bruxelles_Bellone_905.jpg\n| alt              =\n| caption          = A bust of Bellona by Jean Cosyn, a 1697 victory celebration over a Brussels doorway\n| god_of           = Goddess of War, Destruction, Conquest, and Bloodlust\n| abode            = \n| symbol           = Military [[helmet]] and torch\n| consort          = [[Mars (mythology)|Mars]]\n| parents          = [[Jupiter (mythology)|Jupiter]] and [[Juno (mythology)|Juno]]\n| siblings         = [[Mars (mythology)|Mars]], [[Vulcan (mythology)|Vulcan]], [[Juventas]], [[Discordia]], [[Lucina (goddess)|Lucina]]\n| children         = \n| mount            =\n| Greek_equivalent = [[Enyo]]\n}}\n\n'''Bellona''' ({{IPA-la|b\u025bl\u02c8lo\u02d0na|IPA}}) was an [[Ancient Rome|ancient Roman]] goddess of war. Her main attribute is the military [[helmet]] worn on her head; she often holds a sword, spear, or shield, and brandishes a torch or whip as she rides into battle in a four-horse chariot. She had a temple near the [[Theater of Marcellus]]. Her iconography was extended by painters and sculptors following the [[Renaissance]].\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe goddess of war ''Bell\u014dna'' is a derivative of Latin ''bellum'' ('war, warfare'), older ''duellum'', probably stemming from [[Proto-Italic language|Proto-Italic]] ''*duenelo'' ('quite good, quite brave').{{Sfn|de Vaan|2008|p=70}}she was born at belona tower thats why they named her bellona\n\n==Cult and temples==\nOriginally named ''Duellona'' in the [[Italic languages]],<ref>[[Varro]], ''On the Latin Language'', VIII.49.</ref> (according to the typical evolution in Latin of initial \"du\" to \"b\"){{cn|date=February 2020}} the cult figure who became Bellona was an ancient [[Sabines|Sabine]] goddess of war and identified with [[Nerio]], the consort of the war god [[Mars (mythology)|Mars]] - and later with the Greek [[Enyo]]. Her first [[Temple of Bellona (Rome)|temple]] in Rome was dedicated in 296 BCE, where her festival was celebrated on 3 June.<ref>''Encyclopedia of Ancient Mediterranean Religions'' (2016), [https://books.google.com/books?id=dXH4CgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA136 p.136]{{dead link|date=November 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Her priests were known as Bellonarii and used to wound their own arms or legs as a blood sacrifice to her.<ref>William Smith, ''Smaller Classical Dictionary'', London 1862, p.77</ref> These rites took place on 24 March, called the day of blood (''dies sanguinis''), after the ceremony. In consequence of this practice, which approximated to the rites dedicated to [[Cybele]] in [[Asia Minor]], both Enyo and Bellona became identified with her [[Cappadocia]]n aspect, [[Ma (goddess)|Ma]].<ref>\"Cults of Enyo and Ma\" at [http://www.theoi.com/Daimon/Enyo.html Theoi] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160517160833/http://www.theoi.com/Daimon/Enyo.html |date=May 17, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe Roman [[Campus Martius]] area, in which Bellona\u2019s temple was situated, had [[extraterritoriality|extraterritorial status]]. Ambassadors from foreign states, who were not allowed to enter the city proper, stayed in this complex. Since the area of the temple was outside the pomerium, the Senate met there with ambassadors and received victorious generals prior to their [[Roman triumph|triumph]]s. Beside the temple was the war column (''columna bellica''), which represented non-Roman territory. To declare war on a distant state, a javelin was thrown over the column by one of the priests concerned with diplomacy (''[[fetial]]es'') in a modification of the archaic practice, from Roman territory toward the direction of the enemy land and this symbolical attack was considered the opening of war.<ref>\"Fetiales\", [http://www.britannica.com/topic/fetial#ref6592 ''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160801195059/http://www.britannica.com/topic/fetial#ref6592 |date=August 1, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nIn the military cult of Bellona, she was associated with [[Virtus (deity)|Virtus]], the personification of valour. She then travelled outside Rome with the imperial legions and her temples have been recorded in France, Germany, Britain, and North Africa.<ref>Glenys Lloyd-Morgan, \"Nemesis and Bellona\" in ''The Concept of the Goddess'', London 1996, [https://books.google.com/books?id=5Z6EAgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA125 pp.125-6]{{dead link|date=November 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Representation in the arts==\n===Poetry===\nOften in poetry the name Bellona is used simply as a synonym for war, although in the [[Thebaid (Latin poem)|''Thebaid'']] of [[Statius]] the goddess appears as a character, representing the destructive and belligerent aspect of war. There she is described as carrying a spear and a flaming torch or riding in a chariot and waving a blood-stained sword.<ref>Included in the \"Enyo\" article at [http://www.theoi.com/Daimon/Enyo.html Theoi] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160517160833/http://www.theoi.com/Daimon/Enyo.html |date=May 17, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Painting and sculpture===\nBellona is commonly portrayed wearing a plumed helmet and dressed in armour, or at least a [[breastplate]] with a skirt beneath. In her hand she carries a spear, shield, or other weapons, and occasionally, she sounds a [[trumpet]] for the attack. She was sometimes associated with the winged [[Victory]] holding a laurel crown in her hand, a statue of whom she sometimes carries; when she appears on war memorials she may hold that attribute.\n\n==Reception==\n[[File:Spranger Bellona against the Turks.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.05|\"Bellona Leading the Imperial Armies against the Turks\", a 1600 print of [[Bartholomaeus Spranger]]'s  design]]\n\n===Painting and sculpture===\nExamples of such an armoured figure appear in the 1633 painting attributed to [[Rembrandt]] in the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]],<ref>Ernst van de Wetering, A Corpus of Rembrandt Paintings VI: Rembrandt's Paintings Revisited, Dordrecht NL 2014, [https://books.google.com/books?id=Hk5TBQAAQBAJ p.529]{{dead link|date=November 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and statues by [[Johann Baptist Straub]] (1770) and [[Johann Wilhelm Beyer]] (1773\u201380). In the latter she appears with the god [[Janus]], since both were associated with the Roman ceremonies of declaring war. In the case of Janus, the doors to his temple were left open during the whole period of hostilities.\n\n[[File: Bellona Straub.JPG|thumb|upright |right| ''Bellona'', by [[Johann Baptist Straub]], 1770]]\nStraub's statue has a [[gorgon]] head on her shield to instil terror in her enemies, as does the Rembrandt painting, although this was added later, probably as a response to other examples of this new iconographical departure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/437389|title=Rembrandt (Rembrandt van Rijn) - Bellona - The Met|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>  In the bust by [[Bertram Mackennal]] she wears a gorgon mounted on her helmet, while in other depictions it is on the breastplate. Another common innovation was Bellona\u2019s association with cannons, as in the drawing by Hans Krieg (1590\u20131645) <ref>{{cite web|url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Krieg_Bellona.jpg|title=Bellona.|first=Creator:Hans|last=Krieg|date=1 January 1620|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2016|via=Wikimedia Commons}}</ref> and the 1700 ceiling fresco at Hammerschloss Schmidm\u00fchlen by Hans Georg Asam (1649\u20131711).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:ASAM_1.jpg|title=Deutsch: Bellona von Hans Georg Asam, Hammerschloss Schmidm\u00fchlen|first=Klaus Anton|last=Altenbuchner|date=30 November 1899|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2016|via=Wikimedia Commons}}</ref> An early Dutch engraving in a series of prints depicting ''Personifications of Industrial and Professional Life'' suggests that it is this goddess who inspires the invention of war materiels, showing her seated in a factory workshop with all manner of arms at her feet (plate 6, see the Gallery below). In the fresco by Constantino Brumidi in the [[Brumidi Corridors|U.S. Capitol]] (1855\u201360), her image is updated. There she is shown standing next to an [[artillery]] piece and has the stars and stripes on her shield.\n\nNot all representations of Bellona wear armour. The statues by [[Alvise Tagliapietra]] at St. Petersburg (c.1710) and that at the [[J. Paul Getty Museum]] by [[Augustin Pajou]] (1775/85) <ref>[http://www.digital-images.net/Images/Getty-Museum/Sculpture/Modern/Bellona_Pajou_HS4743.jpg Getty Museum site] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402025134/http://www.digital-images.net/Images/Getty-Museum/Sculpture/Modern/Bellona_Pajou_HS4743.jpg |date=April 2, 2015 }}</ref> are largely naked, although otherwise wearing or carrying some of the other attributes of the goddess. There are Classical references that sanction this, however. In [[Gaius Valerius Flaccus]]' ''Argonautica'', for example, appears the description \"Bellona with bare flank, her brazen weapons clanging as she moved\" (3. 60).<ref>\"Bellona\" section at [http://www.theoi.com/Daimon/Enyo.html Theoi] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160517160833/http://www.theoi.com/Daimon/Enyo.html |date=May 17, 2016 }}</ref> A further poetic reference taken up by a painter occurs in [[Louis Jean Fran\u00e7ois Lagren\u00e9e]]'s \"Bellona Presenting the Reins of his Horses to Mars\" (1766). This illustrates a speech from [[Claudian]]'s ''In Ruffinum'' where Mars requests \"Let Bellona bring my helmet and Terror guide the reins\" (''Fer galleam Bellona mihi, nexusque rotarum tende Pavor'').<ref>Quoted in Casimir Simienowicz, ''The great art of artillery'', London 1729, [https://books.google.com/books?id=W0oCAAAAQAAJ&lpg=PA347 p.347]{{dead link|date=November 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> [[Jan van Mieris]]\u2019 allegorical painting of \"Wisdom restraining Bellona\" (1685) is also poetic. There the seated figure of Wisdom clasps the right hand of the helmeted goddess, who is turning to leave, her cloak fluttering behind her and her shield held high in her outstretched left hand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://warburg.sas.ac.uk/vpc/VPC_search/pdf_frame.php?image=00034078|title=WI-ID PDF|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Literature===\nWhile she does not figure as a character in [[Shakespeare]]'s plays, she receives several mentions. In ''[[Henry IV, Part I]]'', Hotspur describes her as \"the fire-eyed maid of smoky war\" (IV.i.119). In [[The Two Noble Kinsmen]], set in pre-Roman Athens, the sister of Hippolyta will solicit her divine aid for Theseus against Thebes (I.iii.13). At the start of the play named after him, ''[[Macbeth]]'' is introduced as a violent and brave warrior when the Thane of Ross calls him \"Bellona's bridegroom\" (I.ii.54), that is to say, the equivalent of Mars. \n \nIn more modern times, [[Adam Lindsay Gordon]] dedicated an energetic [[Algernon Charles Swinburne|Swinburnean]] evocation of the \"false goddess\" who leads men astray in his poem \"Bellona\", published in Australia in 1867.<ref>''Sea Spray and Smoke Drift'', [https://ebooks.adelaide.edu.au/g/gordon/adam_lindsay/poems/chapter1.html#section10 poem 10] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912013537/https://ebooks.adelaide.edu.au/g/gordon/adam_lindsay/poems/chapter1.html#section10 |date=September 12, 2015 }}</ref> She also figures in [[Edgell Rickword]]'s [[World War I]] poem \"The Traveller\". There the poet describes himself as marching toward the front line in the company of Art, the god [[Pan (god)|Pan]], and the works of [[Walter Pater]]. Meeting Bellona as they approach the fighting, one by one the pleasurable companions are forced to flee before the violence of war, until the goddess rejoices in having him to herself.<ref>Published in Behind the Eyes (1921)</ref>\n\n===Cantata and opera===\nBellona appears in the prologue of [[Rameau]]'s opera, ''[[Les Indes Galantes]]'' (1735), in which the call of love ultimately triumphs over that of war.<ref>Cuthbert Girdlestone, Philip Gossett, ''Jean-Philippe Rameau: His Life and Work'', Dover Publications 1969, [https://books.google.com/books?id=7aqtAQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA324 pp.323-4]{{dead link|date=November 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In a Bach ''[[dramma per musica]]'' performed two years before, [[T\u00f6net, ihr Pauken! Erschallet, Trompeten! BWV 214|''T\u00f6net, ihr Pauken! Erschallet, Trompeten!'' BWV 214]], the goddess even quitted her usual ferocity in order to congratulate [[Maria Josepha of Austria]], Princess Elector of Saxony and Queen of Poland, on her birthday on 8 December 1733.<ref>BWV 214, Leipzig 1733; translations of the aria and recitative are on [http://www.emmanuelmusic.org/notes_translations/translations_cantata/t_bwv214.htm Emmanuel Music]}}</ref>\n\nShe retains her harsh aspect in \"Prometheus Absolved\" by [[Giovanni Ambrogio Migliavacca]] (1718\u20131795), however. In this cantata celebrating the birth of the Archduchess Isabella in 1762, the deities sit in judgement on [[Prometheus]], some arguing for clemency, while Bellona and others demand rigour.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_O6t91Maw2i4C|title=Prometeo assoluto serenata cantata in Vienna per comando degli augustissimi regnanti in occasione del felicissimo parto di s.a. reale l'arciduchessa Isabella [Giannambrogio Migliavacca]|first=Giovanni Ambrogio|last=Migliavacca|date=1 January 1762|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2016|via=Internet Archive}}</ref> She also plays her proper part in the 'heroic cantata' created by the composer [[Francesco Bianchi (composer)|Francesco Bianchi]] and the librettist [[Lorenzo da Ponte]], entitled \"The Wedding of the Thames and Bellona\" (''Le nozze del Tamigi e Bellona''). This was performed in London to mark the British naval victory over the Spanish at the [[Battle of Cape St. Vincent (1797)]].<ref>Sheila Hodges, ''Lorenzo Da Ponte: The Life and Times of Mozart's Librettist'', University of Wisconsin 2002, [https://web.archive.org/web/20170621053807/https://books.google.com/books?id=0GpVEvZ5WUgC&lpg=PA150 p.150]</ref>\n\n===Public statements===\nAs well as having a decorative function, representations of the goddess had a public function too. Batholomaeus Spranger's \"Bellona Leading the Imperial Armies against the Turks\" (see above) played its part in Austria's anti-Turkish propaganda during the [[Long Turkish War]]. A later phase of the continuing conflict, culminating in victory at the [[battle of Zenta]] in 1697, is marked by Jean Cosyn's celebratory doorway in Brussels in what now is known as the Maison de Bellone, at the centre of which presides the helmeted bust of the goddess surrounded by military standards and cannons.<ref>Photographs on the [https://web.archive.org/web/20170305005145/http://www.brusselspictures.com/wp-content/photos/Maison-de-la-Bellone/IMG_3203.JPG Brussels Pictures site]</ref>\n\nA dynastic political statement is made in [[Marie de Medici Cycle|\"Marie de Medici as Bellona\"]] (1622/5), designed by [[Peter Paul Rubens]] for her public rooms in the [[Luxembourg Palace]]. He represents her there as a wielder of political power at a time when it, in fact, had waned.<ref>Jane Kromm, The Art of Frenzy: ''Public Madness in the Visual Culture of Europe'', London and New York 2003, [https://books.google.com/books?id=JD35pP8VgUkC&lpg=PA40 p.40]{{dead link|date=November 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> She is standing with armour, cannons, and muskets at her feet, and her triumphs are underlined by emblems of victory. She carries a small statue of the winged goddess in her right hand, a smaller winged figure is mounted below the plumes of her helmet, while [[cupid]]s hover above her, holding a [[laurel crown]]. Her portrayal contrasts with Rembrandt's depiction of Bellona with the homely features of an ordinary Dutchwoman. This makes an anti-imperial statement, with the assurance that the new [[Dutch Republic]] is ready to defend itself, particularly against Spain, during the [[Thirty Years' War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/437389|title=Rembrandt (Rembrandt van Rijn) - Bellona - The Met|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Mus\u00e9e Rodin - Bellone.JPG|thumb|upright=1.1|Auguste Rodin's 1879 bronze bust of Bellona in the Mus\u00e9e Rodin, Paris]]\n[[Auguste Rodin]]'s sculpture of a head of Bellona (1879) originally was created for a monument to the [[French Third Republic]] and shows even more belligerence. Modelled on his mistress Rose Beuret while in a bad mood, the head is drawn back in proud anger, turning in dynamic movement to look along the line of her right shoulder.<ref>Margherita Andreotti, \"Bellona\" in ''Rodin's Art'', OUP USA 2003, [https://books.google.com/books?id=30gpesJe3gwC&lpg=PA53 pp.51-60] {{dead link|date=December 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Defence in war is the message of [[Georg Kolbe]]'s Bellona fountain in [[Wuppertal]]. Originally commissioned in 1915, it depicted the helmeted goddess carrying a sword in her left hand and inspiring a kneeling young man. The statue was not erected until 1922, by which time it functioned as a war memorial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denkmal-wuppertal.de/2011/10/georg-kolbes-brunnen-und-skulptur.html|title=Georg Kolbes Brunnen und Skulptur \"Bellona\" - Denkmal-Wuppertal.de|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe use of Bellona in such structures was well established before this, dating back to her prominent use in Jean Cosyn's doorway. The Temple of Bellona, designed by [[William Chambers (architect)|William Chambers]] for [[Kew Gardens]] in 1760, was projected as a celebration of the Anglo-Hanoverian war effort during the [[Seven Years' War]] and eventually housed plaques honouring the regiments that served in it.<ref>Vanessa Berridge, ''The Princess's Garden: Royal Intrigue and the Untold Story of Kew'', Stroud (Glos.) 2015, [https://books.google.com/books?id=NhpzCgAAQBAJ&lpg=PT180 chapter 15]{{dead link|date=November 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> These, however, related primarily to remembrance of victory rather than of the fallen. It was not until a century afterward that the French-Canadian victims of the Seven Years War were commemorated by a monument at [[Quebec]]. Atop a tall column on the site of the battlefield, Bellona looks down, carrying a shield and laurel crown in her right hand.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Bellone_Monument_des_Braves.jpg|title=Fran\u00e7ais : Statue repr\u00e9sentant Bellone, au sommet du monument des Braves, \u00e0 l'entr\u00e9e du parc des Braves, \u00e0 Qu\u00e9bec (Qu\u00e9bec, Canada). La statue a \u00e9t\u00e9 offerte par le prince J\u00e9r\u00f4me-Napol\u00e9on en 1862. Elle est haute d'environ trois m\u00e8tres et forme le sommet du monument haut de 22 m\u00e8tres. Elle a \u00e9t\u00e9 install\u00e9e, et le monument inaugur\u00e9, le 19 octobre 1863. Elle est peut-\u00eatre inspir\u00e9e d'un croquis d'Eug\u00e8ne-\u00c9tienne Tach\u00e9 [1].|first=Photo|last=Asclepias|date=20 August 2010|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2016|via=Wikimedia Commons}}</ref> The statue was presented by [[Jerome Napoleon Bonaparte II|J\u00e9r\u00f4me-Napol\u00e9on]] in 1862 as a gesture of reconciliation.<ref>[http://www.ccbn-nbc.gc.ca/media/upload/documents/Panneau-ParcdesBraves-CCBN_000.pdf ''Une espace consacr\u00e9e aux braves''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309025030/http://www.ccbn-nbc.gc.ca/media/upload/documents/Panneau-ParcdesBraves-CCBN_000.pdf |date=March 9, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe Australian dead from the [[Gallipoli Campaign]] were commemorated by a bronze bust of Bellona by [[Bertram Mackennal]], a former student of Rodin. This he presented to the Australian government in Canberra as a memorial in 1916.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.davesact.com/2010/06/bellona-goddess-of-war.html|title=BELLONA GODDESS OF WAR|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref> As in Rodin's bust, the helmeted head is turned to the right, but the breasts are more in evidence. The fallen generally make their appearance later in such structures where Bellona is present. They accompany the sword-wielding goddess in [[Douglas Tilden]]'s monument to the California Volunteers during the [[Spanish\u2013American War]] of 1898;<ref>[http://www.artandarchitecture-sf.com/tag/Bellona Art and Architecture] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220183044/http://www.artandarchitecture-sf.com/tag/Bellona |date=February 20, 2016 }}</ref> in the [[Bialystok]] memorial to the dead in the [[Polish\u2013Soviet War in 1920]], she stands behind a soldier and holds aloft a laurel crown.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20151024070221/https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File%3APomnik_ku_czci_poleg%C5%82ym_w_wojnie_Polsko_-_sowieckiej_w_1920_r.jpg Wikimedia Commons]</ref>\n\nThe Bellona on the First World War victory archway at [[London Waterloo railway station|Waterloo station]] is particularly memorable, however. Beneath the demonic sword-brandishing wraith with her gorgon necklace, cower and mourn, not the dead, but the overlooked living victims of war.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blackcablondon.net/category/ww1-100-londons-memorials/page/2/|title=WW1 100: London's Memorials - View from the Mirror - Page 2|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Bellona, by Rembrandt van Rijn.jpg|Bellona in armour, attributed to Rembrandt, 1633\nFile:Peter Paul Rubens - Marie de Medicis as Bellona2.jpg|\"Marie de Medici as Bellona\" by Peter Paul Rubens, 1621\u201325\nFile:Bellona hands Mars his reins Lagren\u00e9e.jpg|''Bellona Presenting the Reins of his Horses to Mars'', Louis Jean Fran\u00e7ois Lagren\u00e9e, 1766\nFile:Bellona-Summer Garden-Saint Petersburg.jpg|Alvise Tagliapietra's unclothed goddess, c. 1710, Saint Petersburg\nFile:N29Janus-u-Bellona.jpg|Janus and Bellona by Johann Wilhelm Beyer, 1773\u201380, Sch\u00f6nbrunn\nFile:Mackennal - War.jpg|Bertram Mackennal 1916 Gallipoli war memorial, Canberra\nFile:Bellona Georg Kolbe.jpg|Georg Kolbe's Wuppertal fountain, 1915/22\nFile:Galle Bellona artificer.jpg|\"Bellona inspires the invention of arms\", Philip Galle, 1574\nFile:Flickr - USCapitol - Bellona, Roman Goddess of War.jpg|Constantino Brumidi's fresco in the U.S. Capitol, 1855\u201360\nFile:VolunteerTrainingCorps Proficiency.jpg|Bellona on the badge of the [[Volunteer Training Corps (World War I)|Volunteer Training Corps]] in [[World War I]]\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n===Bibliography===\n*{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ecZ1DwAAQBAJ|title=Etymological Dictionary of Latin and the other Italic Languages|last=de Vaan|first=Michiel|date=2008|author-link=Michiel de Vaan|publisher=Leiden, Boston|isbn=9789004167971|location=|language=en|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wiktionary|Bellona}}\n{{EB1911 Poster|Bellona}}\n* Images of Bellona in the [http://warburg.sas.ac.uk/vpc/VPC_search/subcats.php?cat_1=5&cat_2=179 Warburg Institute Iconographic Database]\n\n{{Roman religion}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bellona (Goddess)}}\n[[Category:Roman goddesses]]\n[[Category:War goddesses]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Roman goddess of war}}\n{{other uses|Bellona (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox deity\n| type             = Roman\n| name             = Bellona\n| image            = File:Bruxelles_Bellone_905.jpg\n| alt              =\n| caption          = A bust of Bellona by Jean Cosyn, a 1697 victory celebration over a Brussels doorway\n| god_of           = Goddess of War, Destruction, Conquest, and Bloodlust\n| abode            = \n| symbol           = Military [[helmet]] and torch\n| consort          = [[Mars (mythology)|Mars]]\n| parents          = [[Jupiter (mythology)|Jupiter]] and [[Juno (mythology)|Juno]]\n| siblings         = [[Mars (mythology)|Mars]], [[Vulcan (mythology)|Vulcan]], [[Juventas]], [[Discordia]], [[Lucina (goddess)|Lucina]]\n| children         = \n| mount            =\n| Greek_equivalent = [[Enyo]]\n}}\n\n'''Bellona''' ({{IPA-la|b\u025bl\u02c8lo\u02d0na|IPA}}) was an [[Ancient Rome|ancient Roman]] goddess of war. Her main attribute is the military [[helmet]] worn on her head; she often holds a sword, spear, or shield, and brandishes a torch or whip as she rides into battle in a four-horse chariot. She had a temple near the [[Theater of Marcellus]]. Her iconography was extended by painters and sculptors following the [[Renaissance]].\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe goddess of war ''Bell\u014dna'' is a derivative of Latin ''bellum'' ('war, warfare'), older ''duellum'', probably stemming from [[Proto-Italic language|Proto-Italic]] ''*duenelo'' ('quite good, quite brave').{{Sfn|de Vaan|2008|p=70}}\n\n==Cult and temples==\nOriginally named ''Duellona'' in the [[Italic languages]],<ref>[[Varro]], ''On the Latin Language'', VIII.49.</ref> (according to the typical evolution in Latin of initial \"du\" to \"b\"){{cn|date=February 2020}} the cult figure who became Bellona was an ancient [[Sabines|Sabine]] goddess of war and identified with [[Nerio]], the consort of the war god [[Mars (mythology)|Mars]] - and later with the Greek [[Enyo]]. Her first [[Temple of Bellona (Rome)|temple]] in Rome was dedicated in 296 BCE, where her festival was celebrated on 3 June.<ref>''Encyclopedia of Ancient Mediterranean Religions'' (2016), [https://books.google.com/books?id=dXH4CgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA136 p.136]{{dead link|date=November 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Her priests were known as Bellonarii and used to wound their own arms or legs as a blood sacrifice to her.<ref>William Smith, ''Smaller Classical Dictionary'', London 1862, p.77</ref> These rites took place on 24 March, called the day of blood (''dies sanguinis''), after the ceremony. In consequence of this practice, which approximated to the rites dedicated to [[Cybele]] in [[Asia Minor]], both Enyo and Bellona became identified with her [[Cappadocia]]n aspect, [[Ma (goddess)|Ma]].<ref>\"Cults of Enyo and Ma\" at [http://www.theoi.com/Daimon/Enyo.html Theoi] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160517160833/http://www.theoi.com/Daimon/Enyo.html |date=May 17, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe Roman [[Campus Martius]] area, in which Bellona\u2019s temple was situated, had [[extraterritoriality|extraterritorial status]]. Ambassadors from foreign states, who were not allowed to enter the city proper, stayed in this complex. Since the area of the temple was outside the pomerium, the Senate met there with ambassadors and received victorious generals prior to their [[Roman triumph|triumph]]s. Beside the temple was the war column (''columna bellica''), which represented non-Roman territory. To declare war on a distant state, a javelin was thrown over the column by one of the priests concerned with diplomacy (''[[fetial]]es'') in a modification of the archaic practice, from Roman territory toward the direction of the enemy land and this symbolical attack was considered the opening of war.<ref>\"Fetiales\", [http://www.britannica.com/topic/fetial#ref6592 ''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160801195059/http://www.britannica.com/topic/fetial#ref6592 |date=August 1, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nIn the military cult of Bellona, she was associated with [[Virtus (deity)|Virtus]], the personification of valour. She then travelled outside Rome with the imperial legions and her temples have been recorded in France, Germany, Britain, and North Africa.<ref>Glenys Lloyd-Morgan, \"Nemesis and Bellona\" in ''The Concept of the Goddess'', London 1996, [https://books.google.com/books?id=5Z6EAgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA125 pp.125-6]{{dead link|date=November 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Representation in the arts==\n===Poetry===\nOften in poetry the name Bellona is used simply as a synonym for war, although in the [[Thebaid (Latin poem)|''Thebaid'']] of [[Statius]] the goddess appears as a character, representing the destructive and belligerent aspect of war. There she is described as carrying a spear and a flaming torch or riding in a chariot and waving a blood-stained sword.<ref>Included in the \"Enyo\" article at [http://www.theoi.com/Daimon/Enyo.html Theoi] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160517160833/http://www.theoi.com/Daimon/Enyo.html |date=May 17, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Painting and sculpture===\nBellona is commonly portrayed wearing a plumed helmet and dressed in armour, or at least a [[breastplate]] with a skirt beneath. In her hand she carries a spear, shield, or other weapons, and occasionally, she sounds a [[trumpet]] for the attack. She was sometimes associated with the winged [[Victory]] holding a laurel crown in her hand, a statue of whom she sometimes carries; when she appears on war memorials she may hold that attribute.\n\n==Reception==\n[[File:Spranger Bellona against the Turks.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.05|\"Bellona Leading the Imperial Armies against the Turks\", a 1600 print of [[Bartholomaeus Spranger]]'s  design]]\n\n===Painting and sculpture===\nExamples of such an armoured figure appear in the 1633 painting attributed to [[Rembrandt]] in the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]],<ref>Ernst van de Wetering, A Corpus of Rembrandt Paintings VI: Rembrandt's Paintings Revisited, Dordrecht NL 2014, [https://books.google.com/books?id=Hk5TBQAAQBAJ p.529]{{dead link|date=November 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and statues by [[Johann Baptist Straub]] (1770) and [[Johann Wilhelm Beyer]] (1773\u201380). In the latter she appears with the god [[Janus]], since both were associated with the Roman ceremonies of declaring war. In the case of Janus, the doors to his temple were left open during the whole period of hostilities.\n\n[[File: Bellona Straub.JPG|thumb|upright |right| ''Bellona'', by [[Johann Baptist Straub]], 1770]]\nStraub's statue has a [[gorgon]] head on her shield to instil terror in her enemies, as does the Rembrandt painting, although this was added later, probably as a response to other examples of this new iconographical departure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/437389|title=Rembrandt (Rembrandt van Rijn) - Bellona - The Met|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>  In the bust by [[Bertram Mackennal]] she wears a gorgon mounted on her helmet, while in other depictions it is on the breastplate. Another common innovation was Bellona\u2019s association with cannons, as in the drawing by Hans Krieg (1590\u20131645) <ref>{{cite web|url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Krieg_Bellona.jpg|title=Bellona.|first=Creator:Hans|last=Krieg|date=1 January 1620|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2016|via=Wikimedia Commons}}</ref> and the 1700 ceiling fresco at Hammerschloss Schmidm\u00fchlen by Hans Georg Asam (1649\u20131711).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:ASAM_1.jpg|title=Deutsch: Bellona von Hans Georg Asam, Hammerschloss Schmidm\u00fchlen|first=Klaus Anton|last=Altenbuchner|date=30 November 1899|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2016|via=Wikimedia Commons}}</ref> An early Dutch engraving in a series of prints depicting ''Personifications of Industrial and Professional Life'' suggests that it is this goddess who inspires the invention of war materiels, showing her seated in a factory workshop with all manner of arms at her feet (plate 6, see the Gallery below). In the fresco by Constantino Brumidi in the [[Brumidi Corridors|U.S. Capitol]] (1855\u201360), her image is updated. There she is shown standing next to an [[artillery]] piece and has the stars and stripes on her shield.\n\nNot all representations of Bellona wear armour. The statues by [[Alvise Tagliapietra]] at St. Petersburg (c.1710) and that at the [[J. Paul Getty Museum]] by [[Augustin Pajou]] (1775/85) <ref>[http://www.digital-images.net/Images/Getty-Museum/Sculpture/Modern/Bellona_Pajou_HS4743.jpg Getty Museum site] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402025134/http://www.digital-images.net/Images/Getty-Museum/Sculpture/Modern/Bellona_Pajou_HS4743.jpg |date=April 2, 2015 }}</ref> are largely naked, although otherwise wearing or carrying some of the other attributes of the goddess. There are Classical references that sanction this, however. In [[Gaius Valerius Flaccus]]' ''Argonautica'', for example, appears the description \"Bellona with bare flank, her brazen weapons clanging as she moved\" (3. 60).<ref>\"Bellona\" section at [http://www.theoi.com/Daimon/Enyo.html Theoi] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160517160833/http://www.theoi.com/Daimon/Enyo.html |date=May 17, 2016 }}</ref> A further poetic reference taken up by a painter occurs in [[Louis Jean Fran\u00e7ois Lagren\u00e9e]]'s \"Bellona Presenting the Reins of his Horses to Mars\" (1766). This illustrates a speech from [[Claudian]]'s ''In Ruffinum'' where Mars requests \"Let Bellona bring my helmet and Terror guide the reins\" (''Fer galleam Bellona mihi, nexusque rotarum tende Pavor'').<ref>Quoted in Casimir Simienowicz, ''The great art of artillery'', London 1729, [https://books.google.com/books?id=W0oCAAAAQAAJ&lpg=PA347 p.347]{{dead link|date=November 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> [[Jan van Mieris]]\u2019 allegorical painting of \"Wisdom restraining Bellona\" (1685) is also poetic. There the seated figure of Wisdom clasps the right hand of the helmeted goddess, who is turning to leave, her cloak fluttering behind her and her shield held high in her outstretched left hand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://warburg.sas.ac.uk/vpc/VPC_search/pdf_frame.php?image=00034078|title=WI-ID PDF|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Literature===\nWhile she does not figure as a character in [[Shakespeare]]'s plays, she receives several mentions. In ''[[Henry IV, Part I]]'', Hotspur describes her as \"the fire-eyed maid of smoky war\" (IV.i.119). In [[The Two Noble Kinsmen]], set in pre-Roman Athens, the sister of Hippolyta will solicit her divine aid for Theseus against Thebes (I.iii.13). At the start of the play named after him, ''[[Macbeth]]'' is introduced as a violent and brave warrior when the Thane of Ross calls him \"Bellona's bridegroom\" (I.ii.54), that is to say, the equivalent of Mars. \n \nIn more modern times, [[Adam Lindsay Gordon]] dedicated an energetic [[Algernon Charles Swinburne|Swinburnean]] evocation of the \"false goddess\" who leads men astray in his poem \"Bellona\", published in Australia in 1867.<ref>''Sea Spray and Smoke Drift'', [https://ebooks.adelaide.edu.au/g/gordon/adam_lindsay/poems/chapter1.html#section10 poem 10] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912013537/https://ebooks.adelaide.edu.au/g/gordon/adam_lindsay/poems/chapter1.html#section10 |date=September 12, 2015 }}</ref> She also figures in [[Edgell Rickword]]'s [[World War I]] poem \"The Traveller\". There the poet describes himself as marching toward the front line in the company of Art, the god [[Pan (god)|Pan]], and the works of [[Walter Pater]]. Meeting Bellona as they approach the fighting, one by one the pleasurable companions are forced to flee before the violence of war, until the goddess rejoices in having him to herself.<ref>Published in Behind the Eyes (1921)</ref>\n\n===Cantata and opera===\nBellona appears in the prologue of [[Rameau]]'s opera, ''[[Les Indes Galantes]]'' (1735), in which the call of love ultimately triumphs over that of war.<ref>Cuthbert Girdlestone, Philip Gossett, ''Jean-Philippe Rameau: His Life and Work'', Dover Publications 1969, [https://books.google.com/books?id=7aqtAQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA324 pp.323-4]{{dead link|date=November 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In a Bach ''[[dramma per musica]]'' performed two years before, [[T\u00f6net, ihr Pauken! Erschallet, Trompeten! BWV 214|''T\u00f6net, ihr Pauken! Erschallet, Trompeten!'' BWV 214]], the goddess even quitted her usual ferocity in order to congratulate [[Maria Josepha of Austria]], Princess Elector of Saxony and Queen of Poland, on her birthday on 8 December 1733.<ref>BWV 214, Leipzig 1733; translations of the aria and recitative are on [http://www.emmanuelmusic.org/notes_translations/translations_cantata/t_bwv214.htm Emmanuel Music]}}</ref>\n\nShe retains her harsh aspect in \"Prometheus Absolved\" by [[Giovanni Ambrogio Migliavacca]] (1718\u20131795), however. In this cantata celebrating the birth of the Archduchess Isabella in 1762, the deities sit in judgement on [[Prometheus]], some arguing for clemency, while Bellona and others demand rigour.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_O6t91Maw2i4C|title=Prometeo assoluto serenata cantata in Vienna per comando degli augustissimi regnanti in occasione del felicissimo parto di s.a. reale l'arciduchessa Isabella [Giannambrogio Migliavacca]|first=Giovanni Ambrogio|last=Migliavacca|date=1 January 1762|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2016|via=Internet Archive}}</ref> She also plays her proper part in the 'heroic cantata' created by the composer [[Francesco Bianchi (composer)|Francesco Bianchi]] and the librettist [[Lorenzo da Ponte]], entitled \"The Wedding of the Thames and Bellona\" (''Le nozze del Tamigi e Bellona''). This was performed in London to mark the British naval victory over the Spanish at the [[Battle of Cape St. Vincent (1797)]].<ref>Sheila Hodges, ''Lorenzo Da Ponte: The Life and Times of Mozart's Librettist'', University of Wisconsin 2002, [https://web.archive.org/web/20170621053807/https://books.google.com/books?id=0GpVEvZ5WUgC&lpg=PA150 p.150]</ref>\n\n===Public statements===\nAs well as having a decorative function, representations of the goddess had a public function too. Batholomaeus Spranger's \"Bellona Leading the Imperial Armies against the Turks\" (see above) played its part in Austria's anti-Turkish propaganda during the [[Long Turkish War]]. A later phase of the continuing conflict, culminating in victory at the [[battle of Zenta]] in 1697, is marked by Jean Cosyn's celebratory doorway in Brussels in what now is known as the Maison de Bellone, at the centre of which presides the helmeted bust of the goddess surrounded by military standards and cannons.<ref>Photographs on the [https://web.archive.org/web/20170305005145/http://www.brusselspictures.com/wp-content/photos/Maison-de-la-Bellone/IMG_3203.JPG Brussels Pictures site]</ref>\n\nA dynastic political statement is made in [[Marie de Medici Cycle|\"Marie de Medici as Bellona\"]] (1622/5), designed by [[Peter Paul Rubens]] for her public rooms in the [[Luxembourg Palace]]. He represents her there as a wielder of political power at a time when it, in fact, had waned.<ref>Jane Kromm, The Art of Frenzy: ''Public Madness in the Visual Culture of Europe'', London and New York 2003, [https://books.google.com/books?id=JD35pP8VgUkC&lpg=PA40 p.40]{{dead link|date=November 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> She is standing with armour, cannons, and muskets at her feet, and her triumphs are underlined by emblems of victory. She carries a small statue of the winged goddess in her right hand, a smaller winged figure is mounted below the plumes of her helmet, while [[cupid]]s hover above her, holding a [[laurel crown]]. Her portrayal contrasts with Rembrandt's depiction of Bellona with the homely features of an ordinary Dutchwoman. This makes an anti-imperial statement, with the assurance that the new [[Dutch Republic]] is ready to defend itself, particularly against Spain, during the [[Thirty Years' War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/437389|title=Rembrandt (Rembrandt van Rijn) - Bellona - The Met|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Mus\u00e9e Rodin - Bellone.JPG|thumb|upright=1.1|Auguste Rodin's 1879 bronze bust of Bellona in the Mus\u00e9e Rodin, Paris]]\n[[Auguste Rodin]]'s sculpture of a head of Bellona (1879) originally was created for a monument to the [[French Third Republic]] and shows even more belligerence. Modelled on his mistress Rose Beuret while in a bad mood, the head is drawn back in proud anger, turning in dynamic movement to look along the line of her right shoulder.<ref>Margherita Andreotti, \"Bellona\" in ''Rodin's Art'', OUP USA 2003, [https://books.google.com/books?id=30gpesJe3gwC&lpg=PA53 pp.51-60] {{dead link|date=December 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Defence in war is the message of [[Georg Kolbe]]'s Bellona fountain in [[Wuppertal]]. Originally commissioned in 1915, it depicted the helmeted goddess carrying a sword in her left hand and inspiring a kneeling young man. The statue was not erected until 1922, by which time it functioned as a war memorial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denkmal-wuppertal.de/2011/10/georg-kolbes-brunnen-und-skulptur.html|title=Georg Kolbes Brunnen und Skulptur \"Bellona\" - Denkmal-Wuppertal.de|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe use of Bellona in such structures was well established before this, dating back to her prominent use in Jean Cosyn's doorway. The Temple of Bellona, designed by [[William Chambers (architect)|William Chambers]] for [[Kew Gardens]] in 1760, was projected as a celebration of the Anglo-Hanoverian war effort during the [[Seven Years' War]] and eventually housed plaques honouring the regiments that served in it.<ref>Vanessa Berridge, ''The Princess's Garden: Royal Intrigue and the Untold Story of Kew'', Stroud (Glos.) 2015, [https://books.google.com/books?id=NhpzCgAAQBAJ&lpg=PT180 chapter 15]{{dead link|date=November 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> These, however, related primarily to remembrance of victory rather than of the fallen. It was not until a century afterward that the French-Canadian victims of the Seven Years War were commemorated by a monument at [[Quebec]]. Atop a tall column on the site of the battlefield, Bellona looks down, carrying a shield and laurel crown in her right hand.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Bellone_Monument_des_Braves.jpg|title=Fran\u00e7ais : Statue repr\u00e9sentant Bellone, au sommet du monument des Braves, \u00e0 l'entr\u00e9e du parc des Braves, \u00e0 Qu\u00e9bec (Qu\u00e9bec, Canada). La statue a \u00e9t\u00e9 offerte par le prince J\u00e9r\u00f4me-Napol\u00e9on en 1862. Elle est haute d'environ trois m\u00e8tres et forme le sommet du monument haut de 22 m\u00e8tres. Elle a \u00e9t\u00e9 install\u00e9e, et le monument inaugur\u00e9, le 19 octobre 1863. Elle est peut-\u00eatre inspir\u00e9e d'un croquis d'Eug\u00e8ne-\u00c9tienne Tach\u00e9 [1].|first=Photo|last=Asclepias|date=20 August 2010|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2016|via=Wikimedia Commons}}</ref> The statue was presented by [[Jerome Napoleon Bonaparte II|J\u00e9r\u00f4me-Napol\u00e9on]] in 1862 as a gesture of reconciliation.<ref>[http://www.ccbn-nbc.gc.ca/media/upload/documents/Panneau-ParcdesBraves-CCBN_000.pdf ''Une espace consacr\u00e9e aux braves''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309025030/http://www.ccbn-nbc.gc.ca/media/upload/documents/Panneau-ParcdesBraves-CCBN_000.pdf |date=March 9, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe Australian dead from the [[Gallipoli Campaign]] were commemorated by a bronze bust of Bellona by [[Bertram Mackennal]], a former student of Rodin. This he presented to the Australian government in Canberra as a memorial in 1916.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.davesact.com/2010/06/bellona-goddess-of-war.html|title=BELLONA GODDESS OF WAR|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref> As in Rodin's bust, the helmeted head is turned to the right, but the breasts are more in evidence. The fallen generally make their appearance later in such structures where Bellona is present. They accompany the sword-wielding goddess in [[Douglas Tilden]]'s monument to the California Volunteers during the [[Spanish\u2013American War]] of 1898;<ref>[http://www.artandarchitecture-sf.com/tag/Bellona Art and Architecture] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220183044/http://www.artandarchitecture-sf.com/tag/Bellona |date=February 20, 2016 }}</ref> in the [[Bialystok]] memorial to the dead in the [[Polish\u2013Soviet War in 1920]], she stands behind a soldier and holds aloft a laurel crown.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20151024070221/https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File%3APomnik_ku_czci_poleg%C5%82ym_w_wojnie_Polsko_-_sowieckiej_w_1920_r.jpg Wikimedia Commons]</ref>\n\nThe Bellona on the First World War victory archway at [[London Waterloo railway station|Waterloo station]] is particularly memorable, however. Beneath the demonic sword-brandishing wraith with her gorgon necklace, cower and mourn, not the dead, but the overlooked living victims of war.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blackcablondon.net/category/ww1-100-londons-memorials/page/2/|title=WW1 100: London's Memorials - View from the Mirror - Page 2|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Bellona, by Rembrandt van Rijn.jpg|Bellona in armour, attributed to Rembrandt, 1633\nFile:Peter Paul Rubens - Marie de Medicis as Bellona2.jpg|\"Marie de Medici as Bellona\" by Peter Paul Rubens, 1621\u201325\nFile:Bellona hands Mars his reins Lagren\u00e9e.jpg|''Bellona Presenting the Reins of his Horses to Mars'', Louis Jean Fran\u00e7ois Lagren\u00e9e, 1766\nFile:Bellona-Summer Garden-Saint Petersburg.jpg|Alvise Tagliapietra's unclothed goddess, c. 1710, Saint Petersburg\nFile:N29Janus-u-Bellona.jpg|Janus and Bellona by Johann Wilhelm Beyer, 1773\u201380, Sch\u00f6nbrunn\nFile:Mackennal - War.jpg|Bertram Mackennal 1916 Gallipoli war memorial, Canberra\nFile:Bellona Georg Kolbe.jpg|Georg Kolbe's Wuppertal fountain, 1915/22\nFile:Galle Bellona artificer.jpg|\"Bellona inspires the invention of arms\", Philip Galle, 1574\nFile:Flickr - USCapitol - Bellona, Roman Goddess of War.jpg|Constantino Brumidi's fresco in the U.S. Capitol, 1855\u201360\nFile:VolunteerTrainingCorps Proficiency.jpg|Bellona on the badge of the [[Volunteer Training Corps (World War I)|Volunteer Training Corps]] in [[World War I]]\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n===Bibliography===\n*{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ecZ1DwAAQBAJ|title=Etymological Dictionary of Latin and the other Italic Languages|last=de Vaan|first=Michiel|date=2008|author-link=Michiel de Vaan|publisher=Leiden, Boston|isbn=9789004167971|location=|language=en|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wiktionary|Bellona}}\n{{EB1911 Poster|Bellona}}\n* Images of Bellona in the [http://warburg.sas.ac.uk/vpc/VPC_search/subcats.php?cat_1=5&cat_2=179 Warburg Institute Iconographic Database]\n\n{{Roman religion}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bellona (Goddess)}}\n[[Category:Roman goddesses]]\n[[Category:War goddesses]]\n", "name_user": "2601:2c6:4d00:1990:f4d9:9e14:6eed:a164", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEtymology)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bellona_(goddess)"}
{"title_page": "List of DreamWorks Animation programs", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThis is a list of programs by [[DreamWorks Animation]] and its predecessors and acquisitions [[DreamWorks Classics|Classic Media]], [[UPA (animation studio)|UPA]], [[Harvey Comics|Harvey Entertainment]], [[Western Publishing|Golden Books Family Entertainment]], [[Jay Ward Productions]], [[NBCUniversal Television Distribution]], [[Entertainment Rights]], Link Entertainment, [[Tell-Tale Productions]], [[Filmation]], [[Felix the Cat|Felix the Cat Productions]], and [[Chapman Entertainment]]. Most of DWA's library is currently owned by [[Universal Pictures|Universal Studios]] and distributed by [[NBCUniversal Television Distribution]].\n\nNote that some shows were co-productions with other companies and may and/or not necessarily be owned by [[DreamWorks Animation]].\n\n==Series==\n===DreamWorks Animation===\n{{main|List of DreamWorks Animation productions#Television series}}\n\n===Classic Media===\n*''[[Roger Ramjet]]'' (1965)\n*''[[Voltron]]'' (1984\u20131985)\n*''[[Theodore Tugboat]]'' (1993-2001)\n*''[[Voltron: The Third Dimension]]'' (1998\u20132000)\n*''[[Make Way for Noddy]]''\n*''[[Gerald McBoing-Boing (TV series)|Gerald McBoing-Boing]]'' (co-production with [[Teletoon]] and [[Cookie Jar Group]])\n*''[[Lassie's Pet Vet]]'' (2007)\n*''[[George of the Jungle (2007 TV series)|George of the Jungle]]'' (co-production with [[DHX Media]])\n*''[[Olivia (TV series)|Olivia]]''\n*''[[Casper's Scare School (TV series)|Casper's Scare School]]'' (2009-2012)\n*''[[Tinga Tinga Tales]]''\n*''[[My Life Me]]'' (2010-2011)\n*''[[Voltron Force]]'' (2011\u20132012)\n*''[[Noddy in Toyland]]''\n*''[[Postman Pat]]: Special Delivery Service'' (2013, 2016\u20132017) (co-production with Mackinnon and Saunders)\n*''Team Franco'' (2014) (produced by Formula Fun Entertainment)\n*''[[Lassie (2014 TV series)|The New Adventures of Lassie]]'' (2014)\n\n===UPA===\n*''[[The Roy Rogers 