rface Reseller for Second Year in a Row|website=Arizona Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0[[Microsoft]] Worldwide Artificial Intelligence Partner of the Year<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://martechseries.com/sales-marketing/microsoft-announces-2018-partner-of-the-year-winners-and-finalists/|title=Microsoft Announces 2018 Partner of the Year Winners and Finalists|date=2018-06-09|website=MarTechSeries|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0[[Microsoft]] Worldwide Modern Desktop Partner of the Year<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rcpmag.com/blogs/scott-bekker/2018/06/microsoft-partner-of-the-year-2018.aspx|title=Microsoft Names 2018 Partners of the Year -|last=Bekker|first=Scott|last2=Chief|first2=Editor in|website=Redmond Channel Partner|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0[[American City Business Journals|Phoenix Business Journal]] Corporate Philanthropy Volunteerism Finalist<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/phoenix/news/2018/10/25/corporate-philanthropy-2018-insight-enterprise-inc.html|title=Corporate Philanthropy 2018 Volunteerism finalist: Insight Enterprise Inc.|last=|first=|date=|website=www.bizjournals.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\n2019\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0No. 23 on [[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune\u2019s]] 50 Best Workplaces in Technology<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2019/01/17/50-best-workplaces-in-technology/|title=The 50 Best Workplaces in Technology|website=Fortune|language=en|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0No. 430 on the [[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] 500, 11th year of placing<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/fortune500/2019/insight-enterprises|title=Insight Enterprises|website=Fortune|language=en|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Australian IoT Best Primary Industry IoT Project<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iothub.com.au/news/announcing-the-2019-iot-award-winners-526963|title=Announcing the 2019 IoT Award winners|website=IoT Hub|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\n.      No. 70 on [[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] 100 Best Workplaces for Diversity<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/best-workplaces-for-diversity/2019/|title=The 100 Best Workplaces for Diversity|website=Fortune|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Portal|Arizona|Companies}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Tempe, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Software companies based in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in the United States]]\n[[Category:Software companies of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "DragonHawk", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:these shouldn't be capitalized", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Insight_Enterprises"}
{"title_page": "RAF Hawkinge", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2015}}\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox military installation\n| name = RAF Hawkinge<br><s>RFC Hawkinge<br>RFC Folkestone</s>\n| ensign=[[File:Ensign of the Royal Air Force.svg|90px]][[File:RAF type A roundel.svg|50px]]\n| native_name = \n| partof = \n| location = \n| nearest_town = [[Hawkinge]], Kent\n| country = England\n| image = Aircraft of the Royal Air Force, 1939-1945- Supermarine Spitfire. CH5429.jpg\n| caption = Spitfire Mk Vs of No. 91 Squadron lined up at Hawkinge during May 1942\n| coordinates = {{Coord|51|06|45|N|001|09|09|E|region:GB_type:airport|display=inline,title}}\n| type = [[Royal Air Force station]]\n| pushpin_map = Kent\n| pushpin_label = RAF Hawkinge\n| pushpin_map_caption = Shown within Kent\n| ownership = [[Air Ministry]]\n| operator = [[Royal Air Force]] (1918\u20131961)<br>[[Royal Flying Corps]] (1915\u20131918)\n| controlledby = \n| site_area = \n| code = \n| built = {{Start date|1915}}\n| builder = \n| used = October 1915-8 December {{End date|1961}}\n| height = \n| materials = \n| condition = Destroyed\n| fate = Housing estate and museum\n| battles = [[First World War]], [[Second World War]]\n| events = \n| current_commander = <!-- current commander -->\n| past_commanders = <!-- past notable commander(s) -->\n| garrison = \n| occupants = \n| open_to_public = \n| website = \n| IATA = \n| ICAO = \n| FAA = \n| TC = \n| LID = \n| GPS = \n| WMO = \n| elevation = {{Convert|164|m|0}}\n| r1-number =00/00\n| r1-length = <!--{{Convert||m|0}}-->\n| r1-surface =Grass field\n}}\n'''Royal Air Force Hawkinge''' or more simply '''RAF Hawkinge''' is a former [[Royal Air Force]] [[Royal Air Force station|station]] located {{Convert|2.2|mi}} north of [[Folkestone]], Kent and {{Convert|7.1|mi}} west of [[Dover]], Kent, England. The airfield was used by both the [[Royal Flying Corps]] and the [[Royal Air Force]] during its lifetime and was involved during the [[Battle of Britain]] as well other important aerial battles during the [[Second World War]].\n\n==History==\n\n===First World War===\n\nDuring the [[First World War]] the airfield was called RFC Folkestone until 29 December 1916 and RFC Hawkinge later on.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=147}}<ref name=\"ABCT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abct.org.uk/airfields/hawkinge-folkestone |title=Hawkinge (Folkestone) |publisher=Airfields of Britain Conservation Trust|accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref> The only squadron present during this period was [[No. 25 Squadron RAF|No. 25 Squadron RFC]] between 19 and 20 February 1916 with [[Vickers F.B.5]], [[Royal Aircraft Factory F.E.2]]B and [[Morane-Saulnier L]].{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=32}}\n\nAn Aircraft Acceptance Park was in residence between 27 July 1917 and 12 October 1917 before being renamed to No. 12 Aircraft Acceptance Park which stayed until May 1919.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rafweb.org/Stations/Stations-H.htm#Hawkinge|title=RAF Hawkinge|publisher=Air of Authority \u2013 A History of RAF Organisation|accessdate=10 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Inter-war years===\n\nBetween the wars a number of squadrons were posted here:\n* [[No. 2 Squadron RAF|2 Squadron RAF]] between 30 November 1935 and 29 September 1939 with [[Hawker Audax]]es, [[Hawker Hector]]s and [[Westland Lysander]] I .{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=23}}\n* [[No. 17 Squadron RAF|17 Squadron RAF]] reformed here on 1 April 1924 using [[Sopwith Snipe]]s and [[Hawker Woodcock]] II before moving to [[RAF Upavon]] on 14 October 1926.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=29}}\n* [[No. 25 Squadron RAF|25 Squadron RAF]] reformed here on 26 April 1920 with the Snipe before moving to Turkey on 28 September 1922. However the squadron returned on 3 October 1923 still with the Snipe but added the [[Gloster Grebe]] I, [[Armstrong Whitworth Siskin]] IIIA, [[Hawker Fury]] Mk I and II, [[Hawker Demon]] and the [[Gloster Gladiator]]s before being posted to [[RAF Northolt]] on 26 September 1938. 25 Squadron returned again on 12 October 1938 and started using the [[Bristol Blenheim]] IF before the squadron returned to Northolt on 22 August 1939.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=33}}\n* [[No. 38 Squadron RAF|38 Squadron RAF]] from 14 February 1919 until 4 July 1919 when it was disbanded as a cadre.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=37}}\n* [[No. 56 Squadron RAF|56 Squadron RAF]] reformed here on 1 November 1922 with the Snipe before moving to [[RAF Biggin Hill]] on 7 May 1923.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=43}}\n* [[No. 83 Squadron RAF|83 Squadron RAF]] between 14 February 1919 and September 1919 as a cadre.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=50}}\n* [[No. 120 Squadron RAF|120 Squadron RAF]] between 20 February 1919 and 17 July 1919 with the [[Airco DH.9]].{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=58}}\n\n===Second World War===\nIt was from Hawkinge that air liaison was maintained between the Royal Air Force and the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War II)|British Expeditionary Force]] during the [[Battle of France|fighting in France]] and the [[Dunkirk evacuation]] in 1940. As long as communications remained open targets were selected in accordance with requests from the BEF and Hawkinge was one of the advanced re-fuelling bases when maximum range was required for operations over France. It was a fighter airfield for squadrons of No. 11 Group, and was so severely damaged by German bombing and machine gun attacks during the Battle of Britain that it had to be abandoned temporarily.<ref name=cwgc>[http://www.cwgc.org/find-a-cemetery/cemetery/2035818/HAWKINGE%20CEMETERY] CWGC Cemetery Report, Hawkinge Cemetery.</ref>\n\nHawkinge Cemetery is near the site of the aerodrome and most of the 95 Second World War casualties buried there were airmen. About a quarter were killed during the Battle of Britain. Most of the war graves are in a special plot east of the chapel, including 59 German graves, which are together in a group at the south-eastern corner.<ref name=cwgc />\n \nA number of squadrons were posted here:\n* [[No. 1 Squadron RAF|1 Squadron RAF]] as a detachment between 18 June 1940 and 23 July 1940 with the [[Hawker Hurricane]] I.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=23}}\n* [[No. 3 Squadron RAF|3 Squadron RAF]] as a detachment between 13 November 1939 and 28 January 1940 with the Hurricane I.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=24}}\n* [[No. 16 Squadron RAF|16 Squadron RAF]] between 17 February 1940 and 13 April 1940 with the Lysander II.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=29}}\n* [[No. 25 Squadron RAF|25 Squadron RAF]] returned during the Second World War on 10 May 1940 staying for two days still with the Blenheim IF.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=33}}\n* [[No. 26 Squadron RAF|26 Squadron RAF]] between 6 October 1944 and 11 October 1944 with the Hurricane IIC.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=33}}\n* [[No. 41 Squadron RAF|41 Squadron RAF]] initially between 30 June 1942 and 8 July 1942 with the [[Supermarine Spitfire]] VB then again between 12 April 1943 and 21 May 1943 with the Spitfire XII.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=38}}\n* [[No. 65 Squadron RAF|65 Squadron RAF]] between 30 June 1942 and 7 July 1942 with the Spitfire VB.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=45}}\n* [[No. 66 Squadron RAF|66 Squadron RAF]] between 8 October 1942 and 9 October 1942 with the Spitfire VB & VC.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=45}}\n* [[No. 79 Squadron RAF|79 Squadron RAF]] between 1 July 1940 and 11 July 1940 with the Hurricane I.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=49}}\n* [[No. 91 Squadron RAF|91 Squadron RAF]] reformed here on 9 January 1941 with the Spitfire IIA & VB versions until 2 October 1942, however the squadron returned 9 October 1942 this time staying until 23 November 1942. 91 Squadron returned again on 11 January 1943 still with the Spitfire and stayed until 11 January 1943. The squadron returned for the last time on 21 May 1943 with the Spitfire XII and stayed until 28 June 1943 when the squadron moved to [[RAF Westhampnett]].{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=52}}\n* [[No. 124 Squadron RAF|124 Squadron RAF]] between 7 April 1945 and 10 April 1945 with the Spitfire HF IXE.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=58}}\n* [[No. 132 Squadron RAF|132 Squadron RAF]] between 29 September 1944 and 14 December 1944 with the Spitfire IXB.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=59}}\n* [[No. 245 Squadron RAF|245 Squadron RAF]] as a detachment between 12 May 1940 and 20 July 1940 with the Hurricane I.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=77}}\n* [[No. 277 Squadron RAF|277 Squadron RAF]] as a detachment between 7 December 1942 and February 1943 with the Lysander III, [[Supermarine Walrus]] and the [[Boulton Paul Defiant]] I. A detachment returned on 15 April 1944 with [[Supermarine Sea Otter]] before leaving during April 1944. The squadron returned on 5 October 1944 with the Sea Otter, Spitfire VB and the [[Vickers Warwick]] I before disbanded on 15 February 1945.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=82}}\n* [[No. 278 Squadron RAF|278 Squadron RAF]] as a detachment from 15 February 1945 with the Spitfire VB and the Sea Otter during October 1945 when the squadron was disbanded.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=83}}\n* [[No. 313 Squadron RAF|313 Squadron RAF]] between 21 August 1943 and 18 September 1943 with the Spitfire VB.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=86}}\n* [[No. 322 Squadron RAF|322 Squadron RAF]] between 31 December 1943 and 25 February 1944 with the Spitfire VB & VC. The squadron returned with the same aircraft on 1 March 1944 and stayed until 10 March 1944.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=86}}\n* [[No. 350 Squadron RAF|350 Squadron RAF]] initially between 1 October 1943 and 12 October 1943 with the Spitfire VB. 350 Squadron then returned on 31 October 1943 with Spitfire VC and stayed until 30 December 1943. The squadron again on 10 March 1944 with Spitfire IXB and stayed until 14 March 1944. The squadron returned for the last time on 8 August 1944 with Spitfire XIV and stayed until 29 September 1944.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=88}}\n* [[No. 402 Squadron RAF|402 Squadron RCAF]] between 8 August 1944 and 30 September 1944 with Spitfire IX & XIVE.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=89}}\n* [[No. 416 Squadron RAF|416 Squadron RCAF]] between 14 August 1942 and 20 August 1942 with Spitfire VB.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=90}}\n* [[No. 441 Squadron RAF|441 Squadron RCAF]] initially between 1 October 1944 and 30 December 1944 with Spitfire VB & IXB. The squadron returned on 3 April 1945 with Spitfire IX. It left on 29 April 1945.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=92}}\n* [[No. 451 Squadron RAF|451 Squadron RAAF]] between 2 December 1944 and 11 February 1945 with Spitfire IXB & XVI. The squadron returned on 3 May 1945 with Spitfire XVI staying until 17 May 1945.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=93}}\n* [[No. 453 Squadron RAF|453 Squadron RAAF]] between 2 May 1945 and 17 May 1945 with Spitfire LF XVI.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=93}}\n* [[No. 501 Squadron RAF|501 Squadron RAF]] between 8 and 10 October 1942 with Spitfire VB & VC. The squadron returned on 21 June 1943 with Spitfire VB & IX before leaving on 21 January 1944 to [[London Southend Airport|RAF Southend]].{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=94}}\n* [[No. 504 Squadron RAF|504 Squadron RAF]] between 28 February 1945 and 28 March 1945 with Spitfire IXE.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=95}}\n* [[No. 567 Squadron RAF|567 Squadron RAF]] initially as a detachment between 14 November 1944 and 1945 with [[Miles Martinet]], [[Hawker Hurricane]] IV and [[Airspeed Oxford]]. The squadron returned on 13 June 1945 with full squadron strength and replaced the Martinets with the Spitfire XVI. 567 Squadron left on 21 August 1945 going to [[RAF Manston]].{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=97}}\n* [[No. 605 Squadron RAF|605 Squadron RAF]] between 21 May 1940 between 28 May 1940 with Hurricane I.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=99}}\n* [[No. 611 Squadron RAF|611 Squadron RAF]] between 31 December 1944 and 3 March 1945 with Spitfire VII and IX.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=100}}\n* [[No. 613 Squadron RAF|613 Squadron RAF]] as a detachment between November 1939 and April 1940 with Hinds and Hectors.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=100}}\n* [[No. 616 Squadron RAF|616 Squadron RAF]] between 14 August 1942 and 20 August 1942 with Spitfire VI.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=100}}\n\n===Post war===\n\nAfter the war, the station hosted the [[RAF Home Command Gliding Centre]] (part of [[RAF Home Command]]), and is fondly remembered by many Air Cadets as the place where they first learned to fly in Slingsby Mk III and [[Slingsby T.21|Slingsby Sedbergh TX Mk.1]] gliders.\n* [[No. 122 Squadron RAF|122 Squadron RAF]] between 24 September 1945 and 19 October 1945 with the Spitfire IX.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=58}}\n* [[No. 234 Squadron RAF|234 Squadron RAF]] between 27 August 1945 and 21 September with the [[North American P-51 Mustang|North American Mustang IV]].{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=75}}\n* [[No. 658 Squadron RAF|658 Squadron RAF]] between 2 and 6 July 1945 with Auster V.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=103}}\n\nIn the 1950s, RAF Hawkinge became a Woman's Officer Cadet Training Unit, under the command of [[Group Officer]] [[Jean Conan Doyle]], the daughter of Sir [[Arthur Conan-Doyle]]. Group Officer Conan-Doyle went on to become the most senior woman officer in the Royal Air Force with the rank of [[Air Commandant]].\n\nThe Home Command Gliding Centre was ancillary to the training unit, the reason being that the grass airfield made it ideal for ATC Cadets to learn to fly sail planes.\n\n==Station commanders==\n* [[Anne Stephens (WRAF officer)|Anne Stephens]] (1950 to 1952)\n* [[Henrietta Barnett (WRAF officer)|Henrietta Barnett]] (1952 to 1956)\n* [[Jean Conan Doyle]] (1956 to 1959)\n* [[Felicity Hill]] (1959 to 1960)\n\n==Current use==\n\nThe site has been largely built over, but part is occupied by the [[Kent Battle of Britain Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kbobm.org/hawkinge.htm|title=About Former RAF Station Hawkinge|publisher=Kent Battle of Britain Museum|accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Battle of Britain]]\n* [[Battle of Britain Airfields]]\n* [[Battle of Britain RAF squadrons|Battle of Britain Squadrons]]\n* [[List of former Royal Air Force stations]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite book |last1=Jefford |first1= C G |title= RAF Squadrons. A comprehensive record of the movement and equipment of all RAF squadrons and their antecedents since 1912 |year=1988 |publisher= Airlife |location= [[Shrewsbury]] |isbn= 1-85310-053-6 |ref= {{harvid|Jefford|1988}} }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|RAF Hawkinge}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080325212017/http://www.kbobm.org/index.htm Kent Battle of Britain Museum]\n* [http://www.hawkinge.com/INDEX.HTM Hawkinge Village Website]\n\n{{Royal Flying Corps}}\n{{Royal Air Force}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hawkinge}}\n[[Category:Royal Air Force stations in Kent]]\n[[Category:Royal Flying Corps airfields]]\n[[Category:Royal Flying Corps airfields in Kent]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force stations of World War II in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Battle of Britain]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2015}}\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox military installation\n| name = RAF Hawkinge<br><s>RFC Hawkinge<br>RFC Folkestone</s>\n| ensign=[[File:Ensign of the Royal Air Force.svg|90px]][[File:RAF type A roundel.svg|50px]]\n| native_name = \n| partof = \n| location = \n| nearest_town = [[Hawkinge]], Kent\n| country = England\n| image = Aircraft of the Royal Air Force, 1939-1945- Supermarine Spitfire. CH5429.jpg\n| caption = Spitfire Mk Vs of No. 91 Squadron lined up at Hawkinge during May 1942\n| coordinates = {{Coord|51|06|45|N|001|09|09|E|region:GB_type:airport|display=inline,title}}\n| type = [[Royal Air Force station]]\n| pushpin_map = Kent\n| pushpin_label = RAF Hawkinge\n| pushpin_map_caption = Shown within Kent\n| ownership = [[Air Ministry]]\n| operator = [[Royal Air Force]] (1918\u20131961)<br>[[Royal Flying Corps]] (1915\u20131918)\n| controlledby = \n| site_area = \n| code = \n| built = {{Start date|1915}}\n| builder = \n| used = October 1915-8 December {{End date|1961}}\n| height = \n| materials = \n| condition = Destroyed\n| fate = Housing estate and museum\n| battles = [[First World War]], [[Second World War]]\n| events = \n| current_commander = <!-- current commander -->\n| past_commanders = <!-- past notable commander(s) -->\n| garrison = \n| occupants = \n| open_to_public = \n| website = \n| IATA = \n| ICAO = \n| FAA = \n| TC = \n| LID = \n| GPS = \n| WMO = \n| elevation = {{Convert|164|m|0}}\n| r1-number =00/00\n| r1-length = <!--{{Convert||m|0}}-->\n| r1-surface =Grass field\n}}\n'''Royal Air Force Hawkinge''' or more simply '''RAF Hawkinge''' is a former [[Royal Air Force]] [[Royal Air Force station|station]] located {{Convert|2.2|mi}} north of [[Folkestone]], Kent and {{Convert|7.1|mi}} west of [[Dover]], Kent, England. The airfield was used by both the [[Royal Flying Corps]] and the [[Royal Air Force]] during its lifetime and was involved during the [[Battle of Britain]] as well other important aerial battles during the [[Second World War]].\n\n==History==\n\n===First World War===\n\nDuring the [[First World War]] the airfield was called RFC Folkestone until 29 December 1916 and RFC Hawkinge later on.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=147}}<ref name=\"ABCT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abct.org.uk/airfields/hawkinge-folkestone |title=Hawkinge (Folkestone) |publisher=Airfields of Britain Conservation Trust|accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref> The only squadron present during this period was [[No. 25 Squadron RAF|No. 25 Squadron RFC]] between 19 and 20 February 1916 with [[Vickers F.B.5]], [[Royal Aircraft Factory F.E.2]]B and [[Morane-Saulnier L]].{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=32}}\n\nAn Aircraft Acceptance Park was in residence between 27 July 1917 and 12 October 1917 before being renamed to No. 12 Aircraft Acceptance Park which stayed until May 1919.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rafweb.org/Stations/Stations-H.htm#Hawkinge|title=RAF Hawkinge|publisher=Air of Authority \u2013 A History of RAF Organisation|accessdate=10 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Inter-war years===\n\nBetween the wars a number of squadrons were posted here:\n* [[No. 2 Squadron RAF|2 Squadron RAF]] between 30 November 1935 and 29 September 1939 with [[Hawker Audax]]es, [[Hawker Hector]]s and [[Westland Lysander]] I .{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=23}}\n* [[No. 17 Squadron RAF|17 Squadron RAF]] reformed here on 1 April 1924 using [[Sopwith Snipe]]s and [[Hawker Woodcock]] II before moving to [[RAF Upavon]] on 14 October 1926.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=29}}\n* [[No. 25 Squadron RAF|25 Squadron RAF]] reformed here on 26 April 1920 with the Snipe before moving to Turkey on 28 September 1922. However the squadron returned on 3 October 1923 still with the Snipe but added the [[Gloster Grebe]] I, [[Armstrong Whitworth Siskin]] IIIA, [[Hawker Fury]] Mk I and II, [[Hawker Demon]] and the [[Gloster Gladiator]]s before being posted to [[RAF Northolt]] on 26 September 1938. 25 Squadron returned again on 12 October 1938 and started using the [[Bristol Blenheim]] IF before the squadron returned to Northolt on 22 August 1939.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=33}}\n* [[No. 38 Squadron RAF|38 Squadron RAF]] from 14 February 1919 until 4 July 1919 when it was disbanded as a cadre.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=37}}\n* [[No. 56 Squadron RAF|56 Squadron RAF]] reformed here on 1 November 1922 with the Snipe before moving to [[RAF Biggin Hill]] on 7 May 1923.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=43}}\n* [[No. 83 Squadron RAF|83 Squadron RAF]] between 14 February 1919 and September 1919 as a cadre.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=50}}\n* [[No. 120 Squadron RAF|120 Squadron RAF]] between 20 February 1919 and 17 July 1919 with the [[Airco DH.9]].{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=58}}\n\n===Second World War===\nIt was from Hawkinge that air liaison was maintained between the Royal Air Force and the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War II)|British Expeditionary Force]] during the [[Battle of France|fighting in France]] and the [[Dunkirk evacuation]] in 1940. As long as communications remained open targets were selected in accordance with requests from the BEF and Hawkinge was one of the advanced re-fuelling bases when maximum range was required for operations over France. It was a fighter airfield for squadrons of No. 11 Group, and was so severely damaged by German bombing and machine gun attacks during the Battle of Britain that it had to be abandoned temporarily.<ref name=cwgc>[http://www.cwgc.org/find-a-cemetery/cemetery/2035818/HAWKINGE%20CEMETERY] CWGC Cemetery Report, Hawkinge Cemetery.</ref>\n\nHawkinge Cemetery is near the site of the aerodrome and most of the 95 Second World War casualties buried there were airmen. About a quarter were killed during the Battle of Britain. Most of the war graves are in a special plot east of the chapel, including 59 German graves, which are together in a group at the south-eastern corner.<ref name=cwgc />\n \nA number of squadrons were posted here:\n* [[No. 1 Squadron RAF|1 Squadron RAF]] as a detachment between 18 June 1940 and 23 July 1940 with the [[Hawker Hurricane]] I.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=23}}\n* [[No. 3 Squadron RAF|3 Squadron RAF]] as a detachment between 13 November 1939 and 28 January 1940 with the Hurricane I.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=24}}\n* [[No. 16 Squadron RAF|16 Squadron RAF]] between 17 February 1940 and 13 April 1940 with the Lysander II.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=29}}\n* [[No. 25 Squadron RAF|25 Squadron RAF]] returned during the Second World War on 10 May 1940 staying for two days still with the Blenheim IF.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=33}}\n* [[No. 26 Squadron RAF|26 Squadron RAF]] between 6 October 1944 and 11 October 1944 with the Hurricane IIC.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=33}}\n* [[No. 41 Squadron RAF|41 Squadron RAF]] initially between 30 June 1942 and 8 July 1942 with the [[Supermarine Spitfire]] VB then again between 12 April 1943 and 21 May 1943 with the Spitfire XII.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=38}}\n* [[No. 65 Squadron RAF|65 Squadron RAF]] between 30 June 1942 and 7 July 1942 with the Spitfire VB.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=45}}\n* [[No. 66 Squadron RAF|66 Squadron RAF]] between 8 October 1942 and 9 October 1942 with the Spitfire VB & VC.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=45}}\n* [[No. 79 Squadron RAF|79 Squadron RAF]] between 1 July 1940 and 11 July 1940 with the Hurricane I.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=49}}\n* [[No. 91 Squadron RAF|91 Squadron RAF]] reformed here on 9 January 1941 with the Spitfire IIA & VB versions until 2 October 1942, however the squadron returned 9 October 1942 this time staying until 23 November 1942. 91 Squadron returned again on 11 January 1943 still with the Spitfire and stayed until 11 January 1943. The squadron returned for the last time on 21 May 1943 with the Spitfire XII and stayed until 28 June 1943 when the squadron moved to [[RAF Westhampnett]].{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=52}}\n* [[No. 124 Squadron RAF|124 Squadron RAF]] between 7 April 1945 and 10 April 1945 with the Spitfire HF IXE.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=58}}\n* [[No. 132 Squadron RAF|132 Squadron RAF]] between 29 September 1944 and 14 December 1944 with the Spitfire IXB.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=59}}\n* [[No. 245 Squadron RAF|245 Squadron RAF]] as a detachment between 12 May 1940 and 20 July 1940 with the Hurricane I.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=77}}\n* [[No. 277 Squadron RAF|277 Squadron RAF]] as a detachment between 7 December 1942 and February 1943 with the Lysander III, [[Supermarine Walrus]] and the [[Boulton Paul Defiant]] I. A detachment returned on 15 April 1944 with [[Supermarine Sea Otter]] before leaving during April 1944. The squadron returned on 5 October 1944 with the Sea Otter, Spitfire VB and the [[Vickers Warwick]] I before disbanded on 15 February 1945.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=82}}\n* [[No. 278 Squadron RAF|278 Squadron RAF]] as a detachment from 15 February 1945 with the Spitfire VB and the Sea Otter during October 1945 when the squadron was disbanded.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=83}}\n* [[No. 313 Squadron RAF|313 Squadron RAF]] between 21 August 1943 and 18 September 1943 with the Spitfire VB.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=86}}\n* [[No. 322 Squadron RAF|322 Squadron RAF]] between 31 December 1943 and 25 February 1944 with the Spitfire VB & VC. The squadron returned with the same aircraft on 1 March 1944 and stayed until 10 March 1944.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=86}}\n* [[No. 350 Squadron RAF|350 Squadron RAF]] initially between 1 October 1943 and 12 October 1943 with the Spitfire VB. 350 Squadron then returned on 31 October 1943 with Spitfire VC and stayed until 30 December 1943. The squadron again on 10 March 1944 with Spitfire IXB and stayed until 14 March 1944. The squadron returned for the last time on 8 August 1944 with Spitfire XIV and stayed until 29 September 1944.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=88}}\n* [[No. 402 Squadron RAF|402 Squadron RCAF]] between 8 August 1944 and 30 September 1944 with Spitfire IX & XIVE.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=89}}\n* [[No. 416 Squadron RAF|416 Squadron RCAF]] between 14 August 1942 and 20 August 1942 with Spitfire VB.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=90}}\n* [[No. 441 Squadron RAF|441 Squadron RCAF]] initially between 1 October 1944 and 30 December 1944 with Spitfire VB & IXB. The squadron returned on 3 April 1945 with Spitfire IX. It left on 29 April 1945.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=92}}\n* [[No. 451 Squadron RAF|451 Squadron RAAF]] between 2 December 1944 and 11 February 1945 with Spitfire IXB & XVI. The squadron returned on 3 May 1945 with Spitfire XVI staying until 17 May 1945.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=93}}\n* [[No. 453 Squadron RAF|453 Squadron RAAF]] between 2 May 1945 and 17 May 1945 with Spitfire LF XVI.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=93}}\n* [[No. 501 Squadron RAF|501 Squadron RAF]] between 8 and 10 October 1942 with Spitfire VB & VC. The squadron returned on 21 June 1943 with Spitfire VB & IX before leaving on 21 January 1944 to [[London Southend Airport|RAF Southend]].{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=94}}\n* [[No. 504 Squadron RAF|504 Squadron RAF]] between 28 February 1945 and 28 March 1945 with Spitfire IXE.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=95}}\n* [[No. 567 Squadron RAF|567 Squadron RAF]] initially as a detachment between 14 November 1944 and 1945 with [[Miles Martinet]], [[Hawker Hurricane]] IV and [[Airspeed Oxford]]. The squadron returned on 13 June 1945 with full squadron strength and replaced the Martinets with the Spitfire XVI. 567 Squadron left on 21 August 1945 going to [[RAF Manston]].{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=97}}\n* [[No. 605 Squadron RAF|605 Squadron RAF]] between 21 May 1940 between 28 May 1940 with Hurricane I.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=99}}\n* [[No. 611 Squadron RAF|611 Squadron RAF]] between 31 December 1944 and 3 March 1945 with Spitfire VII and IX.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=100}}\n* [[No. 613 Squadron RAF|613 Squadron RAF]] as a detachment between November 1939 and April 1940 with Hinds and Hectors.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=100}}\n* [[No. 616 Squadron RAF|616 Squadron RAF]] between 14 August 1942 and 20 August 1942 with Spitfire VI.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=100}}\n\n===Post war===\n\nAfter the war, the station hosted the [[RAF Home Command Gliding Centre]] (part of [[RAF Home Command]]), and is fondly remembered by many Air Cadets as the place where they first learned to fly in Slingsby Mk III and [[Slingsby T.21|Slingsby Sedbergh TX Mk.1]] gliders.\n* [[No. 122 Squadron RAF|122 Squadron RAF]] between 24 September 1945 and 19 October 1945 with the Spitfire IX.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=58}}\n* [[No. 234 Squadron RAF|234 Squadron RAF]] between 27 August 1945 and 21 September with the [[North American P-51 Mustang|North American Mustang IV]].{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=75}}\n* [[No. 658 Squadron RAF|658 Squadron RAF]] between 2 and 6 July 1945 with Auster V.{{sfn|Jefford|1988|p=103}}\n\nIn the 1950s, RAF Hawkinge became a Woman's Officer Cadet Training Unit, under the command of [[Group Officer]] Conan-Doyle, the daughter of Sir [[Arthur Conan-Doyle]]. Group Officer Conan-Doyle went on to become the most senior woman officer in the Royal Air Force with the rank of [[Air Commandant]].\n\nThe Home Command Gliding Centre was ancillary to the training unit, the reason being that the grass airfield made it ideal for ATC Cadets to learn to fly sail planes.\n\n==Station commanders==\n* [[Anne Stephens (WRAF officer)|Anne Stephens]] (1950 to 1952)\n* [[Henrietta Barnett (WRAF officer)|Henrietta Barnett]] (1952 to 1956)\n* [[Jean Conan Doyle]] (1956 to 1959)\n* [[Felicity Hill]] (1959 to 1960)\n\n==Current use==\n\nThe site has been largely built over, but part is occupied by the [[Kent Battle of Britain Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kbobm.org/hawkinge.htm|title=About Former RAF Station Hawkinge|publisher=Kent Battle of Britain Museum|accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Battle of Britain]]\n* [[Battle of Britain Airfields]]\n* [[Battle of Britain RAF squadrons|Battle of Britain Squadrons]]\n* [[List of former Royal Air Force stations]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite book |last1=Jefford |first1= C G |title= RAF Squadrons. A comprehensive record of the movement and equipment of all RAF squadrons and their antecedents since 1912 |year=1988 |publisher= Airlife |location= [[Shrewsbury]] |isbn= 1-85310-053-6 |ref= {{harvid|Jefford|1988}} }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|RAF Hawkinge}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080325212017/http://www.kbobm.org/index.htm Kent Battle of Britain Museum]\n* [http://www.hawkinge.com/INDEX.HTM Hawkinge Village Website]\n\n{{Royal Flying Corps}}\n{{Royal Air Force}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hawkinge}}\n[[Category:Royal Air Force stations in Kent]]\n[[Category:Royal Flying Corps airfields]]\n[[Category:Royal Flying Corps airfields in Kent]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force stations of World War II in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Battle of Britain]]\n", "name_user": "WikiJon.ca", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePost war:Added link to Jean Conan Doyle page", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RAF_Hawkinge"}
